# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bear-conservation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] US$5 billion in funding for a project called the "Protecting Our Planet Challenge" was announced for the initiative in September 2021.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] In December 2022, 30 by 30 was agreed at the COP15 meeting of the Convention on Biological Diversity, and became a target of the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] This includes the G7 and European Union.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] The initiative has attracted controversy over indigenous rights issues.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] As of May 2026, 17.3% of terrestrial land and inland waters and 9.8% of marine areas are protected.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] Including OECM's (Other Effective Area-based Conservation Measures) the percent of protected areas are 18.4% of terrestrial and inland waters and 10.0% of marine areas.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] The European Commission's Biodiversity strategy for 2030 was proposed on May 20, 2020, as the European Union's contribution to a post-2020 global biodiversity framework.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] The plan includes turning 30% of EU territory to protected area by 2030 and 10% to strictly protected area.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] However as of 2023 EU is not on track to meet the targets.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] The biodiversity strategy is a core part of the European Green Deal, and also intended to support green recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] In July 2023 after many debates the European parliament adopted a version of the Nature restoration law, aiming to restore nature on 20% of the territory of the European Union by 2030.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] In 2024, the European Union passed a nature restoration law aiming to restore 20% of degraded ecosystems by 2030 and 100% by 2050.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] On January 27, 2021, President Joe Biden issued an executive order on "Tackling the Climate Crisis at Home and Abroad".
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] Participating federal agencies included the U.S.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] Department of Commerce, and Council on Environmental Quality.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] The order also established a California Biodiversity Collaborative composed of representatives of government agencies, Native tribes, experts, and other stakeholders.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] The official report, *Pathways to 30x30 California*, was issued by the California Natural Resources Agency on 22 April 2022.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has progressed unevenly, and researchers caution that simply increasing the extent of protected areas is not sufficient to halt biodiversity loss.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] Some conservationists argue that the 30% figure lacks a clear scientific justification and risks being treated as a symbolic or political benchmark rather than a threshold grounded in ecological evidence.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] At the same time, other researchers and advocacy groups contend that 30% may in fact be too low to secure long‑term ecological integrity, and point to proposals such as the "Half‑Earth" concept, which calls for roughly 50% of terrestrial and marine realms to be conserved in some form.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] A further concern relates to the quality and effectiveness of protection once areas are designated.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] Researchers and NGOs have highlighted the persistence of so‑called "paper parks": protected areas that exist in law but lack adequate funding, staffing or enforcement, allowing activities such as poaching, illegal logging, or unregulated development to continue.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] Modelling work by Kuempel et al. suggests that, for exploited species, improving enforcement and management within existing protected areas can in many cases deliver greater conservation benefits than simply expanding the network’s total area without a corresponding increase in resources.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] Taken together, this literature underlines that meeting percentage‑based targets without adequate governance capacity risks diluting scarce conservation resources.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] Other research has examined conditions under which expanding protected areas can still be beneficial even when management budgets do not increase.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] Their results suggest that, in landscapes where human pressures are spatially clumped near reserve boundaries, strategically increasing the size of protected areas can create more secure habitat refuges even without proportional increases in staffing or enforcement.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] In practice, the 30 by 30 commitment has also prompted debate over how "protected" or "conserved" areas are defined for monitoring and reporting purposes.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has also raised concerns about “green grabbing” and green colonialism in the way new protected and conserved areas may be established.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] Similar critiques have been echoed by human rights organisations and researchers who argue that percentage-based conservation targets can replicate earlier "fortress conservation" models if they are implemented through top-down land designations that disregard customary tenure and existing uses.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] More broadly, some Indigenous organisations have criticised the way 30 by 30 has been promoted and negotiated, arguing that it risks appropriating Indigenous lands under the guise of biodiversity conservation.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] The COP15 included 196 parties in negotiations, with competing views regarding the adoption of the 30 by 30 target being wide-spread and well documented.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] The resulting agreement of the conference, the Convention on Biological Diversity, was signed by every party, with the exception of two: the United States and the Vatican.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] Towards the end of the talks, a negotiator from Democratic Republic of the Congo raised objections to the agreement, citing a lack of funding separate from the current Global Environment Facility (GEF).
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] After a delay, COP15 president and Chinese environment minister Huang Runqiu overruled the objection due to a legal technicality, resulting in the passage of the agreement.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] Delegates from the DRC, Cameroon, and Uganda were reportedly displeased with the outcome.
[src:bear-conservation/30-by-30] After the agreement was passed, the DRC's government announced that it would not recognize it as valid.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means re-establishing forest that have either been cut down or lost due to natural causes, such as fire, storm, etc.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Nowadays, the boundaries between afforestation and reforestation projects can be blurred as it may not be so clear what was there before at what point in time.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] An essential aspect of successful afforestation efforts lies in the careful selection of tree species that are well-suited to the local climate and soil conditions.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] By choosing appropriate species, afforested areas can better withstand the impacts of climate change.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Planting and protecting them would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon which is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's current carbon pool.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] However, there has been debate about whether afforestation is beneficial for the sustainable use of natural resources, with some researchers pointing out that tree planting is not the only way to enhance climate mitigation and CO2 capture.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Non-forest areas, such as grasslands and savannas, also benefit the biosphere and humanity, and they need a different management strategy - they are not supposed to be forests.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Afforestation critics argue that ecosystems without trees are not necessarily degraded, and many of them can store carbon as they are; for example, savannas and tundra store carbon underground.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Carbon sequestration estimates in these areas often do not include the total amount of carbon reductions in soils and slowing tree growth over time.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Afforestation can also negatively affect biodiversity by increasing fragmentation and edge effects on the habitat outside the planted area.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Australia, Canada, China, India, Israel, United States and Europe have afforestation programs to increase carbon dioxide removal in forests and in some cases to reduce desertification.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The term afforestation means establishing new forest on lands that were not forest before (e.g. abandoned agriculture).
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The same definition in other words states that afforestation is "conversion to forest of land that historically has not contained forests".
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means the "conversion to forest of land that has previously contained forests but that has been converted to some other use".
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Agroforestry (this is essentially an agricultural activity carried out in order to grow harvestable crops such as fruits and nuts).
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Tree plantations (carried out in order to produce wood and wood-pulp products; this can be seen as an alternative to cutting down naturally occurring forests).
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] However, the term *afforestation* can also "imply the intentional conversion of native non-forest ecosystems to exotic tree cover and violate biodiversity safeguards".
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The process of afforestation begins with site selection.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Several environmental factors of the site must be analyzed, including climate, soil, vegetation, and human activity.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] These factors will determine the quality of the site, what species of trees should be planted, and what planting method should be used.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] After the forest site has been assessed, the area must be prepared for planting.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Preparation can involve a variety of mechanical or chemical methods, such as chopping, mounding, bedding, herbicides, and prescribed burning.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Once the site is prepared, planting can take place.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] One method for planting is direct seeding, which involves sowing seeds directly into the forest floor.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Another is seedling planting, which is similar to direct seeding except that seedlings already have an established root system.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Afforestation by cutting is an option for tree species that can reproduce asexually, where a piece of a tree stem, branch, root, or leaves can be planted onto the forest floor and sprout successfully.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Sometimes special tools, such as a tree planting bar, are used to make planting of trees easier and faster.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] There are several benefits from afforestation such as carbon sequestration, increasing rainfall, prevention of topsoil erosion (from water and wind), flood and landslide mitigation, barriers against high winds, shelter for wildlife, employment and alternative sources of wood products.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Afforestation projects create employment opportunities, particularly in rural areas, thus promoting sustainable livelihoods.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] They can create many jobs in various forest-related activities.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Forests are an important part of the global carbon cycle because trees and plants absorb carbon dioxide through photosynthesis.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Therefore, they play an important role in climate change mitigation.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] By removing the greenhouse gas CO2 from the air, forests function as terrestrial carbon sinks, meaning they store large amounts of carbon in the form of biomass, encompassing roots, stems, branches, and leaves.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] By doing so, forests sequester approximately 25% of human carbon emissions annually, playing a critical role in Earth's climate.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Throughout their lifespan, trees continue to sequester carbon, storing atmospheric CO2 long-term.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Sustainable forest management, afforestation, reforestation are therefore important contributions to climate change mitigation.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] An important consideration in such efforts is that forests can turn from sinks to carbon sources.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In 2019 forests took up a third less carbon than they did in the 1990s, due to higher temperatures, droughts and deforestation.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] National-scale forest inventory data also shows trends from 1999 to 2020 that some forests were already approaching climate thresholds shifting them from carbon sinks to carbon sources.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The typical tropical forest may become a carbon source by the 2060s.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Researchers have found that, in terms of environmental services, it is better to avoid deforestation than to allow for deforestation to subsequently reforest, as the latter leads to irreversible effects in terms of biodiversity loss and soil degradation.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Furthermore, the probability that legacy carbon will be released from soil is higher in a younger boreal forest.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In particular, boreal forests have been noted to support the growth of Armillaria (honey fungus), which is a root pathogen that breaks down compounds necessary for wood integrity, increasing the likelihood of carbon release.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Global greenhouse gas emissions caused by damage to tropical rainforests may have been substantially underestimated until around 2019.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Additionally, the effects of afforestation and reforestation will be farther in the future than keeping existing forests intact.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] It takes much longer − several decades − for the benefits for global warming to manifest to the same carbon sequestration benefits from mature trees in tropical forests and hence from limiting deforestation.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Therefore, scientists consider "the protection and recovery of carbon-rich and long-lived ecosystems, especially natural forests" to be "the major climate solution".
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The planting of trees on marginal crop and pasture lands helps to incorporate carbon from atmospheric CO 2 into biomass.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] For this carbon sequestration process to succeed the carbon must not return to the atmosphere from biomass burning or rotting when the trees die.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Several species of *Ficus* such as *Ficus wakefieldii* have been observed to sequester atmospheric CO2 as calcium oxalate in the presence of oxalotrophic bacteria and fungi, which catabolize the oxalate, which produces calcium carbonate.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The calcium carbonate is precipitated throughout the tree, which also alkalinizes the surrounding soil.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] These species are current candidates for carbon sequestration in agroforestry.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] This Calcium-oxalate fixation process was first observed in the *Iroko* tree, which can sequester up to a ton of calcium carbonate in the soil over its lifespan.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Also Cacti, such as the *Saguaro*, transfer carbon from the biological cycle to the geological cycle by forming the mineral calcium carbonate.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover, although this estimate has been criticized, and the true area that has a net cooling effect on the climate when accounting for biophysical feedbacks like albedo is 20-80% lower.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Planting and protecting these trees would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon if the trees survive future climate stress to reach maturity.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] To put this number into perspective, this is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions (as of 2019) .
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's carbon pool in 2019.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Life expectancy of forests varies throughout the world, influenced by tree species, site conditions, and natural disturbance patterns.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In some forests, carbon may be stored for centuries, while in other forests, carbon is released with frequent stand replacing fires.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Forests that are harvested prior to stand replacing events allow for the retention of carbon in manufactured forest products such as lumber.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] However, only a portion of the carbon removed from logged forests ends up as durable goods and buildings.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The remainder ends up as sawmill by-products such as pulp, paper, and pallets.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] If all new construction globally utilized 90% wood products, largely via adoption of mass timber in low rise construction, this could sequester 700 million net tons of carbon per year.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] This is in addition to the elimination of carbon emissions from the displaced construction material such as steel or concrete, which are carbon-intense to produce.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] A meta-analysis found that mixed species plantations would increase carbon storage alongside other benefits of diversifying planted forests.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Although a bamboo forest stores less total carbon than a mature forest of trees, a bamboo plantation sequesters carbon at a much faster rate than a mature forest or a tree plantation.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Therefore, the farming of bamboo timber may have significant carbon sequestration potential.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that: "The total carbon stock in forests decreased from 668 gigatonnes in 1990 to 662 gigatonnes in 2020".
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In Canada's boreal forests as much as 80% of the total carbon is stored in the soils as dead organic matter.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Impacts on temperature are affected by the location of the forest.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] For example, reforestation in boreal or subarctic regions has less impact on climate.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] This is because it substitutes a high-albedo, snow-dominated region with a lower-albedo forest canopy.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] By contrast, tropical reforestation projects lead to a positive change such as the formation of clouds.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] These clouds then reflect the sunlight, lowering temperatures.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Planting trees in tropical climates with wet seasons has another advantage.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In such a setting, trees grow more quickly (fixing more carbon) because they can grow year-round.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Trees in tropical climates have, on average, larger, brighter, and more abundant leaves than non-tropical climates.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] A study of the girth of 70,000 trees across Africa has shown that tropical forests fix more carbon dioxide pollution than previously realized.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The research suggested almost one-fifth of fossil fuel emissions are absorbed by forests across Africa, Amazonia and Asia.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Afforestation provides other environmental benefits, including increasing the soil quality and its organic carbon levels, reducing the risk of erosion and desertification.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The planting of trees in urban areas is also able to reduce air pollution via the trees' absorption and filtration of pollutants, including carbon monoxide, sulfur dioxide, and ozone, in addition to CO2.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Afforestation protects the biodiversity of plants and animals which allows the sustenance of ecosystems that provide clean air, soil fertilization, etc.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Forests support biodiversity conservation, providing habitats for about 80% of the world's biodiversity and contributing to ecosystem restoration and resilience.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Water management can be improved afforestation, as trees regulate hydrological cycles, reduce soil erosion, and prevent water runoff.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Their capacity to capture and store water helps in mitigating floods and droughts.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Forests act as natural air filters, absorbing pollutants and improving air quality.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Urban forestation projects have been successful in reducing respiratory illnesses and enhancing overall air quality in cities.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Trees provide shade and cooling effects.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] By shading and evaporation, forests can lower local temperatures, offering a more comfortable environment in urban areas and reducing the impact of extreme heat.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Tree-planting campaigns are criticised for sometimes targeting areas where forests would not naturally occur, such as grassland and savanna biomes.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Carbon sequestration forecasts of afforestation programmes often insufficiently consider possible carbon reductions in soils as well as slowing tree growth over time.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Afforestation can negatively affect biodiversity through increasing fragmentation and edge effects for the habitat remaining outside the planted area.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] New forest plantations can introduce generalist predators that would otherwise not be found in open habitat into the covered area, which could detrimentally increase predation rates on the native species of the area.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] A study by scientists at the British Trust for Ornithology into the decline of British populations of Eurasian curlew found that afforestation had impacted curlew populations through fragmentation of their naturally open grassland habitats and increases in generalist predators.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Questions have also been raised in the scientific community regarding how global afforestation could affect the surface albedo of Earth.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The canopy cover of mature trees could make the surface albedo darker, which causes more heat to be absorbed, potentially raising the temperature of the planet.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] This is particularly relevant in parts of the world with high levels of snow cover, due to the significant difference in albedo between highly reflective white snow and darker forest cover which absorbs more solar radiation.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] One significant criticism of reforestation or afforestation efforts that rely on monocultures of - usually conifer - trees is that, while they may increase tree cover, they fail to provide the diverse and complex habitat needed by most woodland creatures.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Monocultures, often planted for commercial purposes or ease of management, lack the biodiversity of natural forests.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] These single-species forests provide limited food sources, shelter, and nesting sites for a wide range of wildlife, and in purely coniferous forests low levels of light may reach the forest floor reducing habitat and variety of plant life.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Many woodland creatures, such as birds, mammals, and insects, rely on a variety of tree species and plant life for survival, and the uniformity of monocultures does not support these varied ecological needs.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] As a result, such reforestation or afforestation efforts may unintentionally create environments that are unsuitable for the very species they aim to protect, thus undermining broader conservation goals.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The Great Green Wall of Africa is a ~5,000 mile forest being planted across the continent to stop the spread of the Sahara Desert to the south.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In Adelaide, South Australia (a city of 1.3 million as of June 2016), Premier Mike Rann (2002 to 2011) launched an urban forest initiative in 2003 to plant 3 million native trees and shrubs by 2014 on 300 project sites across the metro area.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Thousands of Adelaide citizens participated in community planting days on sites including parks, reserves, transport corridors, schools, water courses and coastline.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Only native trees were planted to ensure genetic integrity.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Rann said the project aimed to beautify and cool the city and make it more livable, improve air and water quality, and reduce Adelaide's greenhouse gas emissions by 600,000 tonnes of CO2 per year.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In 2003, the government of Canada created a four-year project called the Forest 2020 Plantation Development and Assessment Initiative, which involved planting 6000 ha of fast-growing forests on non-forested lands countrywide.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] These plantations were used to analyze how afforestation can help to increase carbon sequestration and mitigate greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions while also considering the economic and investment attractiveness of afforestation.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] On 14 December 2020, Canada's Minister of Natural Resources Seamus O'Regan announced the federal government's investment of $3.16 billion to plant two billion trees over the next 10 years.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] This plan aims to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by an estimated 12 megatonnes by 2050.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] China had the highest afforestation rate of any country or region in the world, with 4.77 million hectares (47,000 square kilometers) of afforestation in 2008.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] According to the 2021 government work report, forest coverage will reach 24 percent based on the main targets and tasks for the 14th Five-Year Plan period.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] A law in China from 1981 requires that every school student over the age of 11 plants at least one tree per year.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] From 2011 to 2016, the city Dongying in Shandong province forested over 13,800 hectares of saline soil through the Shandong Ecological Afforestation Project, which was launched with support from the World Bank.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In 2017, the Saihanba Afforestation Community won the UN Champions of the Earth Award in the Inspiration and Action category for "transforming degraded land into a lush paradise".
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The successful afforestation of the Loess Plateau involved collaborative efforts by international and domestic professionals alongside villagers.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Through this initiative, millions of villagers across four of China's poorest provinces were able to improve farming practices and increase incomes and employment, alleviating poverty.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In addition, the careful selection of trees ensured a healthy, self-sustainable ecosystem between tree and soil which facilitated a net carbon sink.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The Loess Plateau, although successful, was costly, reaching almost US$500 million.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] This contrasts with more recent initiatives where the results have not been as favorable.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In an attempt to make afforestation both low-cost and less time-consuming, China shifted towards monoculture of mostly red pine trees.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] However, this did not adequately take into consideration environmental structure and led to increased soil erosion, desertification, sand/dust storms and short-lived trees.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] This has reduced China's environmental sustainability index (ESI) to one of the lowest in the world.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Regarding the effects of afforestation on long-term carbon stocks and carbon sequestration these decrease when trees are less than 5 years old and increase quickly thereafter.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] This means trees from monoculture planting that do not survive never reach full potential for carbon sequestration to offset China's carbon output.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Overall, there is a possibility for afforestation to balance carbon levels and aid carbon neutrality, but several challenges still remain which hinder an all encompassing effort.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The Chinese government requires mining companies to restore the environment around exhausted mines by refilling excavated pits and planting crops or trees.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Many mining companies use these recovered mines for ecotourism business.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Europe deforested more than half of its forested areas over the last 6000 years.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The European Union (EU) has paid farmers for afforestation since 1990, offering grants to turn farmland into forest and payments for the management of forest.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] As part of the Green Deal, the EU program "3 Billion Tree Planting Pledge by 2030" provides direction on afforestation of previous farmland in addition to reforestation.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] According to Food and Agriculture Organization statistics, Spain had the third fastest afforestation rate in Europe in the 1990–2005 period, after Iceland and Ireland.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In those years, a total of 44,360 square kilometers were afforested, and the total forest cover rose from 13.5 to 17.9 million hectares.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In 1990, forests covered 26.6% of the Spanish territory.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] As of 2007, that figure had risen to 36.6%.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Spain today has the fifth largest forest area in the European Union.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] As of 2023 the total forest and tree cover in India was 22%.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The forests of India are grouped into 5 major categories and 16 types based on biophysical criteria.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] 38% of the forest is categorized as subtropical dry deciduous and 30% as tropical moist deciduous and other smaller groups.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In 2016 the Indian government passed the CAMPA (Compensatory Afforestation Fund Management and Planning Authority) law, allowing about 40 thousand crores rupees (almost $6 Billion) to go to Indian states for planting trees.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In 2016 the Maharashtra government planted almost 20,000,000 saplings and pledged to plant another 30,000,000 the following year.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In 2019, 220 million trees were planted in a single day in the Indian state of Uttar Pradesh.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] With wood production as a main objective, monocultures of Aleppo pine were vigorously planted between 1948 and the 1970s.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Following a massive collapse of this species in the 1990s, due to attacks by the insect pine blast scale, the Aleppo pine was gradually replaced by Pinus brutia.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Since the 1990s there has been a trend towards more ecological approaches planting mixed forests combining pines with broadleaf Mediterranean species e.g. oak, pistachio, carob, olive, arbutus and buckthorn.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] About 250 million trees have been planted through the JNF across Israel since 1990.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Tree coverage increased from 2% in 1948 to over 8% at present.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The Japanese temperate rainforest is well sustained and maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] One method that has been utilized in maintaining the health of forests in Japan has been afforestation.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The Japanese government and private businesses have set up multiple projects to plant native tree species in open areas scattered throughout the country.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] This practice has resulted in shifts in forest structure and a healthy temperate rainforest that maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In January 2013, the UK government set a target of 12% woodland cover in England by 2060, up from the then 10%.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In Wales the National Assembly for Wales has set a target of 19% woodland cover, up from 15%.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Government-backed initiatives such as the Woodland Carbon Code are intended to support this objective by encouraging corporations and landowners to create new woodland to offset their carbon emissions.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Charitable groups such as Trees for Life (Scotland) contribute to afforestation and reforestation efforts in the UK.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Afforestation efforts in Scotland have provided an increase in woodland expansion.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] By the 20th century mark, Scotland had diminished woodland coverage to 5% of Scotland's land area.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] However, by the early 21st century, afforestation efforts have increased woodland coverage to 17%.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The Scottish government released their Draft Climate Change Plan in January 2017.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] The 2017 draft plan has increased the targeted woodland coverage to 21% by 2032 and increases the afforestation rate to 15,000 hectares per year.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] In the 1800s people moving westward in the US encountered the Great Plains – land with fertile soil, a growing population and a demand for timber but with few trees to supply it.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] So tree planting was encouraged along homesteads.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Arbor Day was founded in 1872 by Julius Sterling Morton in Nebraska City.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] By the 1930s the Dust Bowl environmental disaster signified a reason for adding significant new tree cover.
[src:bear-conservation/afforestation] Public works programs under the New Deal saw the planting of 18,000 miles of windbreaks stretching from North Dakota to Texas to fight soil erosion (see Great Plains Shelterbelt).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The **American black bear** (***Ursus americanus***), or simply **black bear**, is a species of medium-sized bear which is endemic to North America.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] It is the continent's smallest and most widely distributed bear species.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] It is an omnivore, with a diet varying greatly depending on season and location.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] It typically lives in largely forested areas; it will leave forests in search of food and is sometimes attracted to human communities due to the immediate availability of food.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) lists the American black bear as a least-concern species because of its widespread distribution and a large population, estimated to be twice that of all other bear species combined.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Along with the brown bear (*Ursus arctos*), it is one of the two modern bear species not considered by the IUCN to be globally threatened with extinction.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The American black bear is not closely related to the brown bear or polar bear, though all three species are found in North America; genetic studies reveal that they split from a common ancestor 5.05 million years ago (mya).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] American and Asian black bears are considered sister taxa and are more closely related to each other than to the other modern species of bears.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The ancestors of American black bears and Asian black bears diverged from sun bears 4.58 mya.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The American black bear then split from the Asian black bear 4.08 mya.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] A small, primitive bear genus called protarctos (*U. abstrusus*) is the oldest known North American fossil member of the genus *Ursus*, dated to 4.95 mya.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] This suggests that *U. abstrusus* may be the direct ancestor of the American black bear, which evolved in North America.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The earliest American black bear fossils, from the Early Pleistocene of Port Kennedy, Pennsylvania, greatly resemble the Asian species, though later specimens grew to sizes comparable to grizzly bears.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Once described as a precursor species (*Ursus vitabilis*), these specimens have been synonymized with *U. americanus*.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The American black bear lived during the same period as the giant and lesser short-faced bears (*Arctodus simus* and *A. pristinus*, respectively) and the Florida spectacled bear (*Tremarctos floridanus*).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] These tremarctine bears evolved from bears that had emigrated from Asia to the Americas 7–8 mya.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The giant and lesser short-faced bears are thought to have been heavily carnivorous and the Florida spectacled bear more herbivorous, while the American black bears remained arboreal omnivores, like their Asian ancestors.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] From the Holocene to the present, American black bears seem to have shrunk in size, but this has been disputed because of problems with dating these fossil specimens.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The American black bear's generalist behavior allowed it to exploit a wider variety of foods and has been given as a reason why, of these three genera, it alone survived climate and vegetative changes through the last Ice Age while the other, more specialized North American predators became extinct.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] However, both *Arctodus* and *Tremarctos* had survived several other, previous ice ages.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] After these prehistoric ursids became extinct at the end of the Pleistocene, American black bears, brown bears and polar bears were the only remaining bears in North America.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears are reproductively compatible with several other bear species and occasionally produce hybrid offspring.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] According to Jack Hanna's *Monkeys on the Interstate*, a bear captured in Sanford, Florida, was thought to have been the offspring of an escaped female Asian black bear and a male American black bear.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In 1859, an American black bear and a Eurasian brown bear were bred together in the London Zoo, but the three cubs that were born died before they reached maturity.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] A bear shot in autumn 1986 in Michigan was thought by some to be an American black bear/grizzly bear hybrid, because of its unusually large size and its proportionately larger brain case and skull.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] DNA testing was unable to determine whether it was a large American black bear or a grizzly bear.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Sixteen subspecies are traditionally recognized; however, a 2015 genetic study did not support designating some of these, such as the Florida black bear, as distinct subspecies.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Historically, American black bears occupied the majority of North America's forested regions.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Today, they are primarily limited to sparsely settled, forested areas.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears currently inhabit much of their original Canadian range, though they seldom occur in the southern farmlands of Alberta, Saskatchewan and Manitoba; they have been extirpated on Prince Edward Island since 1937.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Surveys taken in the mid-1990s found the Canadian black bear population to be between 396,000 and 476,000 in seven provinces; this estimate excludes populations in New Brunswick, the Northwest Territories, Nova Scotia and Saskatchewan.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] All provinces indicated stable populations of American black bears over the 2000s.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The current range in the United States is constant throughout most of the Northeast and within the Appalachian Mountains almost continuously from Maine to northern Georgia, the northern Midwest, the Rocky Mountain region, the West Coast and Alaska.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] However, it becomes increasingly fragmented or absent in other regions.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Despite this, American black bears in those areas seem to have expanded their range in recent decades, such as with sightings in Ohio, Illinois, southern Indiana, and western Nebraska.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Sightings of itinerant black bears in the Driftless Area of southeastern Minnesota, northeastern Iowa, and southwestern Wisconsin are common.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In 2019, biologists with the Iowa Department of Natural Resources confirmed documentation of an American black bear living year-round in woodlands near the town of Decorah in northeastern Iowa, believed to be the first instance of a resident black bear in Iowa since the 1880s.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Surveys taken from 35 states in the early 1990s indicated that American black bear populations were either stable or increasing, except in Idaho and New Mexico.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The population in the United States was estimated to range between 339,000 and 465,000 in 2011, though this estimate does not include data from Alaska, Idaho, South Dakota, Texas or Wyoming, whose populations were not recorded in the survey.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In California there were an estimated 25,000-35,000 black bears in 2017, making it the largest population of the species in any of the 48 contiguous United States.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In 2020 there were about 1,500 bears in Great Smoky Mountains National Park, where the population density is about two per square mile.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In western North Carolina, the black bear population has dramatically increased from about 3,000 in the early 2000s to over 8,000 in the 2020s.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] As of 1993, known black bear populations in Mexico existed in four areas, though knowledge on the distribution of populations outside those areas has not been updated since 1959.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Mexico is the only country where the species is classified as "endangered".
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Throughout their range, habitats preferred by American black bears have a few shared characteristics.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] They are often found in areas with relatively inaccessible terrain, thick understory vegetation and large quantities of edible material (especially masts).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Although found in the largest numbers in wild, undisturbed areas and rural regions, American black bears can adapt to surviving in some numbers in peri-urban regions, as long as they contain easily accessible foods and some vegetative coverage.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In most of the contiguous United States, American black bears today are usually found in heavily vegetated mountainous areas, from 400 to 3,000 m (1,300 to 9,800 ft) in elevation.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] For American black bears living in the American Southwest and Mexico, habitat usually consists of stands of chaparral and Pinyon–juniper woodlands.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In this region, bears occasionally move to more open areas to feed on prickly pear cactus.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] At least two distinct, prime habitat types are inhabited in the Southeastern United States.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears in the southern Appalachian Mountains survive in predominantly oak-hickory and mixed mesophytic forests.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In the coastal areas of the southeast (such as Florida, the Carolinas and Louisiana), bears inhabit a mixture of flatwoods, bays and swampy hardwood sites.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In the northeastern part of the range (the United States and Canada), prime habitat consists of a forest canopy of hardwoods such as beech, maple, birch and coniferous species.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Corn crops and oak-hickory mast are also common sources of food in some sections of the northeast; small, thick swampy areas provide excellent refuge cover largely in stands of white cedar.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Along the Pacific coast, redwood, Sitka spruce and hemlocks predominate as overstory cover.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Within these northern forest types are early successional areas important for American black bears, such as fields of brush, wet and dry meadows, high tidelands, riparian areas and a variety of mast-producing hardwood species.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The spruce-fir forest dominates much of the range of the American black bear in the Rockies.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Important non-forested areas here are wet meadows, riparian areas, avalanche chutes, roadsides, burns, sidehill parks and subalpine ridgetops.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In areas where human development is relatively low, such as stretches of Canada and Alaska, American black bears tend to be found more regularly in lowland regions.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In parts of eastern Canada, especially Labrador, American black bears have adapted exclusively to semi-open areas that are more typical habitat in North America for brown bears (likely due to the absence there of brown and polar bears, as well as other large carnivore species).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] showing top, bottom and lateral aspects.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The skulls of American black bears are broad, with narrow muzzles and large jaw hinges.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In Virginia, the length of adult bear skulls was found to average 26.2 to 31.7 cm (10.3 to 12.5 in).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Across its range, the longest reported skull measured from 23.5 to 35 cm (9.3 to 13.8 in).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Sexual dimorphism can be seen in the tendency for females to have slenderer and more pointed faces, and conversely, for larger cheek teeth in males.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Their claws are short and curved, being thickest at the base then tapering to a point, and most often black or grayish-brown in color.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Claws from both hind and front legs are almost identical in length, though the curvature of foreclaws tends to be greater.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The soles of the feet are black or brownish and are naked, leathery and deeply wrinkled.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The hind legs are relatively longer than those of Asian black bears.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The ears are small and rounded, as well as being set well back on the head.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears are highly dexterous, being capable of opening screw cap containers and manipulating door latches.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] They also have great physical strength; a bear weighing 120 lb (54 kg) was observed flipping over flat rocks weighing 310 to 325 lb (141 to 147 kg) with a single foreleg.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] They move with a rhythmic, sure-footed gait and can run at speeds of up to 25–30 mph (40–48 km/h).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears have good eyesight and have been proven experimentally to be able to learn visual color discrimination tasks faster than chimpanzees and just as fast as domestic dogs.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] They are also capable of rapidly learning to distinguish different shapes, such as small triangles, circles and squares.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Adults typically range from 120 to 188 cm (47 to 74 in) in head-and-body length, and 63 to 103.5 cm (24.8 to 40.7 in) in shoulder height.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Although the American black bear is the smallest bear species in North America (smaller than the brown and polar bears), large males exceed the size of other bear species in other continents.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Weight tends to vary according to age, sex, health and season.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Adult males typically weigh between 60–300 kg (130–660 lb) with females averaging between 33% and 50% less at 40–150 kg (88–331 lb).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Seasonal variation in weight is very pronounced: in autumn, their pre-den weight tends to be 30% higher than in spring, when black bears emerge from their dens.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In California, studies indicate that the average adult mass is 86 kg (190 lb) in males and 58 kg (128 lb) in females.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Adults in Yukon Flats National Wildlife Refuge in east-central Alaska were found to average 87.3 kg (192 lb) in males and 63.4 kg (140 lb) in females, whereas on Kuiu Island in southeastern Alaska (where nutrient dense salmon are readily available) adults averaged 115 kg (254 lb).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In Great Smoky Mountains National Park, adult males averaged 112 kg (247 lb) and adult females averaged 47 kg (104 lb) per one study.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In one of the largest studies on regional body mass, bears in British Columbia averaged 73.7 kg (162 lb) in 89 females and 103.1 kg (227 lb) in 243 males.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In Yellowstone National Park, a study found that adult males averaged 119 kg (262 lb) and adult females averaged 67 kg (148 lb).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Black bears in north-central Minnesota averaged 70 kg (150 lb) in 163 females and 125 kg (276 lb) in 77 males.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In New York, the males average 136 kg (300 lb) and females 72.6 kg (160 lb).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In Waterton Lakes National Park, Alberta, adults averaged 125 to 128 kg (276 to 282 lb).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The biggest wild American black bear ever recorded was a male from New Brunswick, shot in November 1972, that weighed 409 kg (902 lb) after it had been dressed, meaning it weighed an estimated 500 kg (1,100 lb) in life and measured 2.41 m (7 ft 11 in) long.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Another notably outsized wild American black bear, weighing in at 408 kg (899 lb), was the cattle-killer shot in December 1921 on the Moqui Reservation in Arizona.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The record-sized American black bear from New Jersey was shot in Morris County December 2011 and scaled 376.5 kg (830 lb).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The Pennsylvania state record weighed 399 kg (880 lb) and was shot in November 2010 in Pike County.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The North American Bear Center, located in Ely, Minnesota, is home to the world's largest captive male and female American black bears.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Honey, the female, weighed 219.6 kg (484 lb) in the fall of 2007.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The fur is soft, with dense underfur and long, coarse, thick guard hairs.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The fur is not as shaggy or coarse as that of brown bears.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] American black bear skins can be distinguished from those of Asian black bears by the lack of a white blaze on the chest and hairier footpads.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Despite their name, black bears show a great deal of color variation.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Individual coat colors can range from white, blonde, cinnamon, light brown or dark chocolate brown to jet black, with many intermediate variations existing.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Silvery-gray American black bears with a blue luster (found mostly on the flanks) occur along a portion of coastal Alaska and British Columbia.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] White to cream-colored American black bears occur in the coastal islands and the adjacent mainland of southwestern British Columbia.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Albino individuals have also been recorded.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Black coats tend to predominate in humid areas, such as Maine, New England, New York, Tennessee, Michigan and western Washington.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Approximately 70% of all American black bears are black, though only 50% in the Rocky Mountains are black.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Many in northwestern North America are cinnamon, blonde or light brown in color and thus may sometimes be mistaken for grizzly bears.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Grizzly (and other types of brown) bears can be distinguished by their shoulder hump, larger size and broader, more concave skull.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Their keenest sense is smell, which is about seven times more sensitive than a domestic dog's.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] They are excellent and strong swimmers, swimming for pleasure and to feed (largely on fish).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] They regularly climb trees to feed, escape enemies and hibernate.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Four of the eight modern bear species are habitually arboreal (the most arboreal species, the American and Asian black bears and the sun bear, being fairly closely related).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Their arboreal abilities tend to decline with age.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] They may be active at any time of the day or night, although they mainly forage by night.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Bears living near human habitations tend to be more extensively nocturnal, while those living near brown bears tend to be more often diurnal.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears tend to be territorial and non-gregarious in nature.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] However, at abundant food sources (e.g. spawning salmon or garbage dumps), they may congregate and dominance hierarchies form, with the largest, most powerful males dominating the most fruitful feeding spots.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] They mark their territories by rubbing their bodies against trees and clawing at the bark.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Annual ranges held by mature male bears tend to be very large, though there is some variation.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] On Long Island off the coast of Washington, ranges average 5 sq mi (13 km2), whereas on the Ungava Peninsula in Canada ranges can average up to 1,000 sq mi (2,600 km2), with some male bears traveling as far as 4,349 sq mi (11,260 km2) at times of food shortages.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Bears may communicate with various vocal and non-vocal sounds.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Tongue-clicking and grunting are the most common sounds and are made in cordial situations to conspecifics, offspring and occasionally humans.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] When at ease, they produce a loud rumbling hum.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] During times of fear or nervousness, bears may moan, huff or blow air.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Warning sounds include jaw-clicking and lip-popping.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In aggressive interactions, black bears produce guttural pulsing calls that may sound like growling.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Cubs squeal, bawl or scream when anxious and make a motor-like humming sound when comfortable or nursing.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears often mark trees using their teeth and claws as a form of communication with other bears, a behavior common to many species of bears.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Sows usually produce their first litter at the age of 3 to 5 years, with those living in more developed areas tending to get pregnant at younger ages.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The breeding period usually occurs in the June–July period, though it can extend to August in the species' northern range.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The breeding period lasts for two to three months.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Males try to mate with several females, but large, dominant ones may violently claim a female if another mature male comes near.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Sows tend to be short-tempered with their mates after copulating.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The fertilized eggs undergo delayed development and do not implant in the female's womb until November.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The gestation period lasts 235 days, and litters are usually born in late January to early February.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Litter size is between one and six cubs, typically two or three.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] They are born with fine, gray, down-like hair and their hind quarters are underdeveloped.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] They typically open their eyes after 28–40 days and begin walking after 5 weeks.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Cubs are dependent on their mother's milk for 30 weeks and will reach independence at 16–18 months.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] At 6 weeks, they attain 900 g (2.0 lb), by 8 weeks they reach 2.5 kg (5.5 lb) and by 6 months they weigh 18 to 27 kg (40 to 60 lb).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] They reach sexual maturity at 3 years and attain their full growth at 5 years.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The average lifespan in the wild is 18 years, and it is quite possible for wild individuals to survive for more than 23 years.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The record age of a wild individual was 39 years, while that in captivity was 44 years.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The average annual survival rate is variable, ranging from 86% in Florida to 73% in Virginia and North Carolina.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In Minnesota, 99% of wintering adult bears were able to survive the hibernation cycle in one study.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] A study of American black bears in Nevada found that the amount of annual mortality of a population of bears in wilderness areas was 0%, whereas in developed areas in the state this figure rose to 83%.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Survival in subadults is generally less assured.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In Alaska 14–17% of subadult males and 30–48% of subadult females were found in a study to survive to adulthood.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Across the range, the estimated number of cubs who survive past their first year is 60%.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] With the exception of the rare confrontation with an adult brown bear or a gray wolf pack, adult black bears are not usually subject to natural predation.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Scats with fur inside of them and a carcass of an adult sow with puncture marks in the skull indicate black bears may occasionally be killed by jaguars in the southern parts of their range.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In such scenarios, the big cat would have the advantage if it ambushed the bear, killing it with a crushing bite to the back of the skull.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Cubs tend to be more vulnerable to predation than adults, with known predators including bobcats, coyotes, cougars, gray wolves, brown bears and other bears of their own species.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Many of these will stealthily snatch small cubs right from under the sleeping mother.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] There is record of a golden eagle snatching a yearling cub.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Once out of hibernation, mother bears may be able to fight off most potential predators.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Even cougars will be displaced by an angry mother bear if they are discovered stalking the cubs.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Flooding of dens after birth may also occasionally kill newborn cubs.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Bear fatalities are mainly attributable to human activities.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Seasonally, thousands of black bears are hunted legally across North America, and some are illegally poached or trapped unregulated.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Auto collisions also may kill many black bears annually.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears are now considered highly efficient hibernators.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The physiology of American black bears in the wild is closely related to that of bears in captivity.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Understanding the physiology of bears in the wild is vital to the bear's success in captivity.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The bears enter their dens in October and November, although in the southernmost areas of their range (i.e.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Florida, Mexico, the southeastern United States), only pregnant females and mothers with yearling cubs will enter hibernation.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Prior to that time, they can put on up to 14 kg (30 lb) of body fat to get them through the several months during which they fast.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Hibernation typically lasts 3–8 months, depending on regional climate.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Hibernating bears spend their time in hollowed-out dens in tree cavities, under logs or rocks, in banks, caves, or culverts, and in shallow depressions.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Although naturally-made dens are occasionally used, most dens are dug out by the bear.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] During their time in hibernation, an American black bear's heart rate drops from 40 to 50 beats per minute to 8 beats per minute, and the metabolic rate can drop to a quarter of the bear's (non-hibernating) basal metabolic rate.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] These reductions in metabolic rate and heart rate do not appear to decrease the bear's ability to heal injuries during hibernation.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Their circadian rhythm stays intact during hibernation.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] This allows the bear to sense the changes in the day based on the ambient temperature caused by the sun's position in the sky.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] It has also been shown that ambient light exposure and low disturbance levels (that is to say, wild bears in ambient light conditions) directly correlate with their activity levels.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The bear keeping track of the changing days allows it to awaken from hibernation at the appropriate time of year to conserve as much energy as possible.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The hibernating bear does not display the same rate of muscle and bone atrophy relative to other nonhibernatory animals that are subject to long periods of inactivity due to ailment or old age.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] A hibernating bear only loses approximately half the muscular strength compared to that of a well-nourished, inactive human.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The bear's bone mass does not change in geometry or mineral composition during hibernation, which implies that the bear's conservation of bone mass during hibernation is caused by a biological mechanism.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] During hibernation American black bears retain all excretory waste, leading to the development of a hardened mass of fecal material in the colon known as a fecal plug.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Leptin is released into the bear's systems to suppress appetite.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The retention of waste during hibernation (specifically in minerals such as calcium) may play a role in the bear's resistance to atrophy.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The body temperature does not drop significantly, like other mammalian hibernators (staying around 35 °C (95 °F)) and they remain somewhat alert and active.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] If the winter is mild enough, they may wake up and forage for food.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Females also give birth in February and nurture their cubs until the snow melts.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] During winter, American black bears consume 25–40% of their body weight.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Researchers have found that bears have adaptive reversible insulin resistance.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] During their fattening phase bears become hypersensitive to insulin but in the winter they switch and become more insulin resistant, as well as activating anti-inflammatory genes to resist kidney damage.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Many of the physiological changes an American black bear exhibits during hibernation are retained slightly post-hibernation.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Upon exiting hibernation, bears retain a reduced heart rate and basal metabolic rate.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The metabolic rate of a hibernating bear will remain at a reduced level for up to 21 days after hibernation.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] After emerging from their winter dens in spring, they wander their home ranges for two weeks so that their metabolism accustoms itself to the activity.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In mountainous areas, they seek southerly slopes at lower elevations for forage and move to northerly and easterly slopes at higher elevations as summer progresses.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The time that American black bears emerge from hibernation varies.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Factors affecting this include temperature, flooding, and hunger.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In southern areas, they may wake up in midwinter.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Further north, they may not be seen until late March, April, or even early May.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Bears at lower altitudes tend to emerge earlier.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Mature males tend to come out earliest, followed by immature males and females, and lastly mothers with cubs.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Mothers with yearling cubs are seen before those with newborns.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Generally, American black bears are largely crepuscular in foraging activity, though they may actively feed at any time.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Up to 85% of their diet consists of vegetation, though they tend to dig less than brown bears, eating far fewer roots, bulbs, corms and tubers than the latter species.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] When initially emerging from hibernation, they will seek to feed on carrion from winter-killed animals and newborn ungulates.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] As the spring temperature warms, American black bears seek new shoots of many plant species, especially new grasses, wetland plants and forbs.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Young shoots and buds from trees and shrubs during the spring period are important to bears emerging from hibernation, as they assist in rebuilding muscle and strengthening the skeleton and are often the only digestible foods available at that time.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] During summer, the diet largely comprises fruits, especially berries and soft mast such as buds and drupes.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] During the autumn hyperphagia, feeding becomes virtually the full-time task.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Hard mast becomes the most important part of the diet in autumn and may even partially dictate the species' distribution.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Favored mast such as hazelnuts, oak acorns and whitebark pine nuts may be consumed by the hundreds each day by a single bear during the fall.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] During the fall period, bears may also habitually raid the nut caches of tree squirrels.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Also extremely important in fall are berries such as huckleberries and buffalo berries.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Bears living in areas near human settlements or around a considerable influx of recreational human activity often come to rely on foods inadvertently provided by humans, especially during summertime.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] These include refuse, birdseed, agricultural products and honey from apiaries.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The majority of the animal portion of their diet consists of insects, such as bees, yellow jackets, ants, beetles and their larvae.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears are also fond of honey and will gnaw through trees if hives are too deeply set into the trunks for them to reach it with their paws.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Once the hive is breached, the bears will scrape the honeycombs together with their paws and eat them, regardless of stings from the bees.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Bears that live in northern coastal regions (especially the Pacific Coast) will fish for salmon during the night, as their black fur is easily spotted by salmon in the daytime.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Other bears, such as the white-furred Kermode bears of the islands of western Canada, have a 30% greater success rate in catching salmon than their black-furred counterparts.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Other fish, including suckers, trout and catfish, are readily caught whenever possible.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Although American black bears do not often engage in active predation of other large animals for much of the year, the species will regularly prey on mule and white-tailed deer fawns in spring, given the opportunity.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Bears may catch the scent of hiding fawns when foraging for something else and then sniff them out and pounce on them.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] As the fawns reach 10 days of age, they can outmaneuver the bears, and their scent is soon ignored until the next year.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears have also been recorded similarly preying on elk calves in Idaho and moose calves in Alaska.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Predation on adult deer is rare, but it has been recorded.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] They may even hunt prey up to the size of adult female moose, which are considerably larger than themselves, by ambushing them.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] There is at least one record of a male American black bear killing two bull elk over the course of six days by chasing them into deep snow banks, which impeded their movements.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] In Labrador, American black bears are exceptionally carnivorous, living largely off caribou, usually young, injured, old, sickly or dead specimens, and rodents such as voles.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] This is believed to be due to a paucity of edible plant life in this sub-Arctic region and a local lack of competing large carnivores (including other bear species).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Like brown bears, American black bears try to use surprise to ambush their prey and target the weak, injured, sickly or dying animals in the herds.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Once a deer fawn is captured, it is frequently torn apart alive while feeding.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] If it is able to capture a mother deer in spring, the bear frequently begins feeding on the udder of lactating females, but generally prefers meat from the viscera.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Bears often drag their prey to cover, preferring to feed in seclusion.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The skin of large prey is stripped back and turned inside out, with the skeleton usually left largely intact.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Unlike gray wolves and coyotes, bears rarely scatter the remains of their kills.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Vegetation around the carcass is usually matted down, and their droppings are frequently found nearby.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Bears may attempt to cover remains of larger carcasses, though they do not do so with the same frequency as cougars and grizzly bears.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] They will readily consume eggs and nestlings of various birds and can easily access many tree nests, even the huge nests of bald eagles.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Bears have been reported stealing deer and other game from human hunters.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Over much of their range, American black bears are assured scavengers that can intimidate, using their large size and considerable strength, and if necessary dominate other predators in confrontations over carcasses.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] However, on occasions where they encounter Kodiak or grizzly bears, the larger two brown subspecies dominate them.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears tend to escape competition from brown bears by being more active in the daytime and living in more densely forested areas.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Violent interactions, resulting in the deaths of American black bears, have been recorded in Yellowstone National Park.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears do occasionally compete with cougars over carcasses.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Like brown bears, they will sometimes steal kills from cougars.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] One study found that both bear species visited 24% of cougar kills in Yellowstone and Glacier National Parks, usurping 10% of the carcasses.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Another study found that American black bears visited 48% of cougar kills in summer in Colorado and 77% of kills in California.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] As a result, the cats spend more time killing and less time feeding on each kill.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] American black bear interactions with gray wolves are much rarer than with brown bears, due to differences in habitat preferences.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] The majority of American black bear encounters with wolves occur in the species' northern range, with no interactions being recorded in Mexico.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Despite the American black bear being more powerful on a one-to-one basis, packs of wolves have been recorded to kill black bears on numerous occasions without eating them.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Unlike brown bears, American black bears frequently lose against wolves in disputes over kills.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Wolf packs typically kill American black bears when the larger animals are in their hibernation cycle.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] There is at least one record of an American black bear killing a wolverine (*Gulo gulo*) in a dispute over food in Yellowstone National Park.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] Anecdotal cases of alligator predation on American black bears have been reported, though such cases may involve assaults on cubs.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p01] At least one jaguar (*Panthera onca*) has been recorded to have attacked and eaten a black bear: "El Jefe", the jaguar famous for being the first jaguar seen in the United States in over a century.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Black bears feature prominently in the stories of some of North America's indigenous peoples.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] One tale tells of how the black bear was a creation of the Great Spirit, while the grizzly bear was created by the Evil Spirit.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] In the mythology of the Haida, Tlingit and Tsimshian people of the northwest coast, mankind first learned to respect bears when a girl married the son of a black bear chieftain.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] In Kwakwa̱ka̱ʼwakw mythology, black and brown bears became enemies when Grizzly Bear Woman killed Black Bear Woman for being lazy.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Black Bear Woman's children, in turn, killed Grizzly Bear Woman's children.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] The Navajo believed that the Big Black Bear was chief among the bears of the four directions surrounding Sun's house and would pray to it in order to be granted its protection during raids.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Sleeping Bear Dunes in Michigan is named after a Native American legend, where a female bear and her two cubs swam across Lake Michigan to escape a fire on the Wisconsin shore.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] The mother bear reached the shore and waited for her cubs, but they did not make it across.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Two islands mark where the cubs drowned, while the dune marks the spot where the mother bear waited.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Richard Steiff, the creator of the teddy bear, made the toy in 1902 under Margarete Steiff's felt goods company.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] The toys were brought to the US and gained mass popularity after a newspaper told the story of Theodore Roosevelt refusing to shoot a black bear cub tied to a tree.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] The fictional character Winnie-the-Pooh was named after Winnipeg, a female cub that lived at the London Zoo from 1915 until her death in 1934.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] A cub, who in the spring of 1950 was caught in the Capitan Gap Fire, was made into the living representative of Smokey Bear, the mascot of the United States Forest Service.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Terrible Ted was a de-toothed and de-clawed bear who was forced to perform as a pro wrestler and whose "career" lasted from the 1950s to the 1970s.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Clark's Bears, previously named Clark's Trading Post, is a visitor attraction in Lincoln, New Hampshire known for its trained bear shows since 1949.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] The American black bear is the mascot of the University of Maine and Baylor University, the latter of which houses two live bears on campus.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Although an adult bear is quite capable of killing a human, American black bears typically avoid confronting humans.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Unlike grizzly bears, which became a subject of fearsome legend among the European settlers of North America, black bears were rarely considered overly dangerous, even though they lived in areas where the pioneers had settled.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] American black bears rarely attack when confronted by humans and usually only make mock charges, emit blowing noises and swat the ground with their forepaws.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] The number of attacks on humans is higher than those by brown bears in North America, but this is largely because black bears considerably outnumber brown bears.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Compared to brown bear attacks, aggressive encounters with black bears rarely lead to serious injury.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Most attacks tend to be motivated by hunger rather than territoriality and thus victims have a higher probability of surviving by fighting back rather than submitting.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Unlike female brown bears, female American black bears are not as protective of their cubs and rarely attack humans in the vicinity of the cubs.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] However, occasionally such attacks do occur.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] The worst recorded attack occurred in May 1978, in which a bear killed three teenagers fishing in Algonquin Provincial Park in Ontario.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Another exceptional attack occurred in August 1997 in Liard River Hot Springs Provincial Park in British Columbia, when an emaciated bear attacked a mother and child, killing the mother and a man who intervened.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] The bear was shot while mauling a fourth victim.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] The majority of attacks happened in national parks, usually near campgrounds, where the bears had habituated too close to human proximity and food.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Of 1,028 incidents of aggressive acts toward humans, recorded from 1964 to 1976 in the Great Smoky Mountains National Park, 107 resulted in injury and occurred mainly in tourist hot spots where people regularly fed the bears handouts.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] In almost every case where open garbage dumps that attracted bears were closed and handouts ceased, the number of aggressive encounters dropped.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] However, in the Liard River Hot Springs case, the bear was apparently dependent on a local garbage dump that had closed and so was starving to death.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Attempts to relocate bears are typically unsuccessful, as the bears seem able to return to their home range, even without familiar landscape cues.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] A limitation of food sources in early spring and wild berry and nut crop failures in summer may contribute to bears regularly feeding from human-based food sources.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] These bears often eat crops, especially during autumn hyperphagia when natural foods are scarce.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Favored crops include apples, oats and corn.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] American black bears can do extensive damage in areas of the northwestern United States by stripping the bark from trees and feeding on the cambium.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Livestock depredations occur mostly in spring.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Although they occasionally hunt adult cattle and horses, they seem to prefer smaller prey such as sheep, goats, pigs and young calves.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] They usually kill by biting the neck and shoulders, though they may break the neck or back of the prey with blows with the paws.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Evidence of a bear attack includes claw marks and is often found on the neck, back and shoulders of larger animals.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Surplus killing of sheep and goats is common.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] American black bears have been known to frighten livestock herds over cliffs, causing injuries and death to many animals; whether this is intentional is not known.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Occasionally bears kill pets, especially domestic dogs, which are most prone to harass a bear.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] It is not recommended to use unleashed dogs to deter bear attacks.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Although large, aggressive dogs can sometimes cause a bear to run, if pressed, angry bears often turn the tables and end up chasing the dogs in return.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] A bear in pursuit of a pet dog can threaten both canid and human lives.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] The hunting of American black bears has taken place since the initial peopling of the Americas.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] The first piece of evidence dates to a Clovis site at Lehner Ranch, Arizona.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Partially calcined teeth of a 3-month old black bear cub came from a roasting pit, suggesting the bear cub was eaten.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] The surrounding charcoal was dated to the Early Holocene (10,940 BP).
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Black bear remains also appear to be associated with early peoples in Tlapacoya, Mexico.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Native Americans increasingly utilized black bears during the Holocene, particularly in the late Holocene upper Midwest, e.g., Hopewell and Mississippian cultures.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Some Native American tribes, in admiration for the American black bear's intelligence, would decorate the heads of bears they killed with trinkets and place them on blankets.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Tobacco smoke would be wafted into the disembodied head's nostrils by the hunter that dealt the killing blow, who would compliment the animal for its courage.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] The Kutchin typically hunted American black bears during their hibernation cycle.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Unlike the hunting of hibernating grizzly bears, which was fraught with danger, hibernating American black bears took longer to awaken and hunting them was thus safer and easier.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] During the European colonization of eastern North America, thousands of bears were hunted for their meat, fat and fur.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] He wrote that black bears were difficult to hunt by stalking, due to their habitat preferences, though they were easy to trap.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Roosevelt described how, in the southern states, planters regularly hunted bears on horseback with hounds.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] General Wade Hampton was known to have been present at 500 successful bear hunts, two-thirds of which he killed personally.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] He killed 30 or 40 bears with only a knife, which he would use to stab the bears between the shoulder blades while they were distracted by his hounds.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Unless well trained, horses were often useless in bear hunts, as they often bolted when the bears stood their ground.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] In 1799, 192,000 American black bear skins were exported from Quebec.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] In 1822, 3,000 skins were exported from the Hudson's Bay Company.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] In 1992, untanned, fleshed and salted hides were sold for an average of $165.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] In Canada, black bears are considered as both a big game and furbearer species in all provinces, save for New Brunswick and the Northwest Territories, where they are only classed as a big game species.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] There are around 80,900 licensed bear hunters in Canada.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Canadian black bear hunts take place in the fall and spring, and both male and female bears can be legally taken, though some provinces prohibit the hunting of females with cubs, or yearlings.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Currently, 28 of the U.S. states have American black bear hunting seasons.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Nineteen states require a bear hunting license, with some also requiring a big game license.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] In eight states, only a big game license is required.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Overall, over 481,500 American black bear hunting licenses are sold per year.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] The hunting methods and seasons vary greatly according to state, with some bear hunting seasons including fall only, spring and fall, or year-round.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] New Jersey, in November 2010, approved a six-day bear-hunting season in early December 2010 to slow the growth of the population.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Bear hunting had been banned in New Jersey for five years before that time.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] A Fairleigh Dickinson University PublicMind poll found that 53% of New Jersey voters approved of the new season if scientists concluded that bears were leaving their usual habitats and destroying private property.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Men, older voters and those living in rural areas were more likely to approve of a bear hunting season in New Jersey than women, younger voters and those living in more developed parts of the state.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] In the western states, where there are large American black bear populations, there are spring and year-round seasons.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Approximately 18,000 American black bears were killed annually in the U.S. between 1988 and 1992.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Within this period, annual kills ranged from six bears in South Carolina to 2,232 in Maine.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] According to Dwight Schuh in his *Bowhunter's Encyclopedia*, American black bears are the third most popular quarry of bowhunters, behind deer and elk.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Bear meat had historically been held in high esteem among North America's indigenous people and colonists.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] American black bears were the only bear species the Kutchin hunted for their meat, though this constituted only a small part of their diet.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] — *Frank Forester's Field Sports of the United States, and British Provinces, of North America*, p.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Theodore Roosevelt likened the flesh of young American black bears to that of pork, and not as coarse or flavorless as the meat of grizzly bears.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] The most favored cuts are concentrated in the legs and loins.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Meat from the neck, front legs and shoulders is usually ground into minced meat or used for stews and casseroles.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Keeping the fat on tends to give the meat a strong flavor.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] As American black bears can have trichinosis, cooking temperatures need to be high in order to kill the parasites.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] Bear fat was once valued as a cosmetic article that promoted hair growth and gloss.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] The fat most favored for this purpose was the hard white fat found in the body's interior.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] As only a small portion of this fat could be harvested for this purpose, the oil was often mixed with large quantities of hog lard.
[src:bear-conservation/american-black-bear-p02] However, animal rights activism over the last decade has slowed the harvest of these animals; therefore the lard from bears has not been used in recent years for the purpose of cosmetics.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx (*Oryx leucoryx*), also called the white oryx, was extinct in the wild as of 1972, but was reintroduced to the wild starting in 1982.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The initial reintroduction was primarily from two herds: the "World Herd" originally started at the Phoenix Zoo in 1963 from only nine oryx and the Saudi Arabian herd started in 1986 from private collections and some "World Herd" stock by the Saudi National Wildlife Research Center (NWRC).
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009, there have been reintroductions in Oman, Saudi Arabia, Israel, the United Arab Emirates, and Jordan, and as of 2013 the IUCN Red List classifies the species as vulnerable.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx was known to be in decline since the early 1900s in the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] By the 1930, there were two separate populations isolated from each other.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Talbot reported that Arabian oryx appeared to be extinct in its former range along the southern edge of Ar-Rub' al-Khali.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] He believed that any oryx still existing would be exterminated within the next few years and recommended that a captive breeding program be started to save the species.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Michael Crouch, then Assistant Adviser in the Eastern Aden Protectorate, drew attention to the fact that each spring, small groups of oryx still emerged onto the gravel plains in the northeast corner of the Protectorate, where he thought a capture attempt would be possible.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The initial plan of the Fauna and Flora Preservation Society was to establish a herd in Kenya where another species of oryx already lived and flourished.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Kenyan plan was dropped because of an outbreak of hoof-and-mouth disease, and the oryx destined for Kenya were shipped to the Phoenix Zoo instead.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] There were originally four individuals captured and seven donated for this project.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The four were captured in Aden (now Yemen) near the border of Oman by an expedition led by the late Major Ian Grimwood, then chief game warden of Kenya, with help from Manahil and Mahra tribesmen.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] One male from this group later died of capture stress.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The seven donated oryx were: one from the London Zoo, two from Sheikh Jaber Abdullah al-Sabah, and two pairs from the collection of King Saud bin Abdul Aziz.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Five Arabian oryx were delivered to the Phoenix Zoo in 1963 (four in June and one in September).
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] A baby was born to the herd in October 1963 from a conception en route and another was born in spring 1964, bringing the starting population of the Phoenix Zoo herd to seven.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The four oryx donated by King Saud arrived at the Phoenix Zoo in July 1964, bringing the population of the "World Herd" to 11.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The breeding program at the Phoenix Zoo was very successful, and the zoo celebrated its 225th Arabian oryx birth in 2002.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] From Phoenix, individuals were sent to other zoos and parks (including the San Diego Wild Animal Park) to start their herds.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Most of the Arabian oryx in the wild today have ancestors from the Phoenix Zoo.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Reintroductions started in 1982 in Oman.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009 there have been reintroductions in Oman, Saudi Arabia, Israel, the United Arab Emirates, and Jordan.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] At this time, populations in the United Arab Emirates and Jordan are still not considered in the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) Red List wild oryx count.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The population in Oman is still receiving supplementary forage, and the introduction into Jordan was after the last update of the Red List.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] By 1980, the number of Arabian oryx in captivity had increased to the point that reintroduction to Oman was attempted from the San Diego Wild Animal Park to Jaaluni in the Jiddat al-Harasis.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The oryx were initially kept in large pens outdoors, but were released to the wild on January 31, 1982, in the Omani Central Desert and Coastal Hills.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] These oryx became the core of the Oman herd in the wild, though there were several other releases of captive bred animals over the next two decades.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The area of their release became the Arabian Oryx Sanctuary.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] On June 28, 2007, Oman's Arabian Oryx Sanctuary was the first site to be removed from the UNESCO World Heritage List.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] UNESCO cited the Omani government's decision to open 90% of the site to oil prospecting as the main reason for this decision.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx population on the site has been reduced from 450 oryx in 1996 to only 65 in 2007, mostly due to poaching and illegal live capture.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] There are now fewer than four breeding pairs left on the site.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Organized captive breeding of the Arabian oryx in Saudi Arabia began in April 1986, when 57 oryx from the farm of the late King Khalid bin Abdul Aziz in King Khalid Wildlife Research Center were brought to the National Wildlife Research Center (NWRC) near At-Ta'if.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Between the initial 1986 founding and 1996, 33 additional oryx (including some from the "World Herd") have been introduced to the founder generation of Arabian oryx at the NWRC.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Since 1996, all additions to the population have been through births.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Due to an outbreak of *Mycobacterium bovis* (bovine tuberculosis) in the founder generation, a "buffer generation" was introduced in the herd.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Since then, calves produced by the founder herd are removed from their dam immediately after birth and hand-reared.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] These hand-reared second generation oryx are regularly tested for tuberculosis and a variety of other pathogenic agents, and join the breeding nucleus only when tests are consecutively negative.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] After breeding, they produce the third generation of oryx, which are tuberculosis free and mother-reared, and of which more than 80% are reintroduced into the wild.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Reintroduction of a wild population began in 1995 in the 'Uruq Bani Ma'arid Protected Area.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The reserve covers about 12,000 km2 (4,600 sq mi) at the western edge of the Rubʿ al-Khali desert or "Empty Quarter".
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009, the IUCN Red List estimates the oryx population on this reserve at 160 individuals.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] A free ranging herd was established in the newly created Mahazat as-Sayd Protected Area in 1989.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] This 2,244 km2 (866 sq mi) fenced reserve is home to reintroduced oryx, gazelle and the houbara bustard.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009, the IUCN Red List estimates the oryx population on this reserve at about 800 individuals.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In Israel the reintroduction program was established in 1978 when four pairs of Arabian oryx were purchased.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] At this time the IUCN Redbook reported wild populations totaling 90–100 animals in three locations in Northern Arava and the Negev Desert.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2014 there are around 130 animals in the Aravah, and in 2013 they began to spread to the central Negev and the population keeps increasing.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In addition to the natural population increase, every year around six animals are released to the wild in Israel.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Israel is the only country in which the Arabian oryx was reintroduced where poaching prohibition can be enforced, and because of this the Israeli population grows annually.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Apart from the wild oryx population in Israel, there are a few dozen oryx in the Yotvata Hai-Bar Nature Reserve, a few breeding couples in the Jerusalem Biblical Zoo and a small herd in the Ramat Gan Safari.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The reintroduction of oryx in Israel is one of a few successful programs reintroducing animals into nature in Israel; others include the introduction of the Persian onager (a proxy for the extinct Syrian onager), and the very successful reintroduction of Persian fallow deer.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In the early 1960s, the late Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan directed the capture of two breeding pairs of the oryx for the nucleus of a captive-breeding program in Al Ain, which would lead to the formation of the city's zoo.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In 2007 the United Arab Emirates started releasing animals into Umm Al Zumul.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009 there have been about 100 animals released.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As part of this initiative, a similar program is being developed to reintroduce this extinct species into its natural habitats in Yemen and Iraq.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Since March 1999, the Emirate of Abu Dhabi has been host to an inter-governmental body known as The Coordinating Committee for the Conservation of the Arabian Oryx, which oversees the coordination of conservation efforts for this species within the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In 2012, GSCAO carried out an Arabian Oryx Disease Survey which was funded by the Environment Agency – Abu Dhabi (EAD), in the range states.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx are periodically released in protected areas, such as the Qasr Al Sarab Protected Area.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2017, it is estimated that around 10,000 Arabian oryx, of which 5,000 are estimated to be in Abu Dhabi, are currently in the United Arab Emirates.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The reintroduction project for Jordan began when the Environment Agency of Abu Dhabi (EAD) and the Al Aqaba Special Economic Zone Authority signed a sponsorship agreement in April 2007.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Under this agreement, EAD is sponsoring the million three-year project which includes reintroduction of the Arabian oryx into the Wadi Rum Protected Area, rehabilitating the habitat, and helping local residents to improve their living standards.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Twenty oryx (12 males and 8 females) were released into the Wadi Rum Protected Area in July 2009.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In 1986, as a result of the reintroduction efforts, the IUCN re-listed the Arabian oryx from extinct in the wild to endangered.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] By 2009, the Arabian oryx was protected by law in all areas where it appears.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In June 2011, the Arabian oryx was re-listed as vulnerable by the IUCN Red List.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In 2016 the IUCN estimated there were more than 1000 Arabian oryx in the wild, with 6000–7000 held in captivity worldwide in zoos, preserves, and private collections.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Some of these are in large fenced enclosures (free-roaming), including those in Syria (Al Talila), Bahrain, Qatar, and UAE.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] This is the first time the IUCN has re-classified a species as vulnerable after it had been listed as extinct in the wild.
[src:bear-conservation/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx is also listed in CITES Appendix I.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The **Asian black bear** (***Ursus thibetanus***), also known as the **Asiatic black bear**, **moon bear** and **white-chested bear**, is a medium-sized bear species native to Asia that is largely adapted to an arboreal lifestyle.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It is distributed from southeastern Iran, Pakistan, India and the Himalayas to mainland Southeast Asia, the Korean Peninsula, Taiwan, mainland China and the Russian Far East to the islands of Honshū and Shikoku in Japan.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It is listed as vulnerable on the IUCN Red List, and is threatened by deforestation and poaching for its body parts, which are used in traditional medicine.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Biologically and morphologically, the Asian black bear represents the beginning of the arboreal specializations attained by sloth bears and sun bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It has karyotypes nearly identical to those of the five other ursine bears, and has 74 chromosomes.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It is considered the least derived of the Old World bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It is either a surviving, albeit modified, form of *Ursus etruscus*, specifically the early, small variety of the Middle Villafranchian or a larger form of *Ursus minimus*, an extinct species that arose 4 million years ago.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] With the exception of the age of the bones, it is often difficult to distinguish the remains of *Ursus minimus* with those of the modern Asian black bear.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Asian black bear and the American black bear are thought to have genetically diverged 3 million years ago, though genetic evidence is inconclusive.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Both the American and Asian black species are considered sister taxa and are more closely related to each other than to the other bear species.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The earliest known Asian black bear specimens are known from the early Pliocene in Moldova.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The earliest American black bear fossils found in Pennsylvania greatly resemble the Asian black bear.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Until the Late Pleistocene, two further subspecies ranged across Europe and West Asia.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] These are *U. t. mediterraneus* from Western Europe and the Caucasus and *U. t. permjak* from Eastern Europe, particularly the Ural Mountains.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears are reproductively compatible with several other bear species, and have on occasion produced hybrid offspring.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In 1975, within Venezuela's "Las Delicias" Zoo, a female Asian black bear shared her enclosure with a male spectacled bear, and produced several hybrid descendants.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In 2005, a possible Asian black bear–sun bear hybrid cub was captured in the Mekong River watershed of eastern Cambodia.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] An Asian black bear/brown bear hybrid, taken from a bile farm, is housed at the Animals Asia Foundation's China Moon Bear Rescue as of 2010.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Asian black bear has black fur, a light brown muzzle, and a distinct whitish or creamy patch on the chest, which is sometimes V-shaped.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Its ears are bell shaped, proportionately longer than those of other bears, and stick out sideways from the head.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Its tail is short, around 11 cm (4.3 in) long.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Adult males weigh 60–200 kg (130–440 lb) with an average weight of about 135 kg (298 lb).
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Asian black bear is similar in general build to the brown bear (*Ursus arctos*), but is lighter and smaller.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The lips and nose are larger and more mobile than those of brown bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The skull of the Asian black bear is relatively small but massive, particularly in the lower jaw.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Although the Asian black bear is mostly herbivorous, its jaw structure is not as specialized for plant eating as that of the giant panda; Asian black bears have much narrower zygomatic arches, and the weight ratio of the two pterygoid muscles is also much smaller in Asian black bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The lateral slips of the temporal muscles are thicker and stronger in Asian black bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In contrast to the polar bear, the Asian black bear has a powerful upper body for climbing trees, and relatively weak hind legs which are shorter than those in the brown bear and American black bear.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] An Asian black bear with broken hind legs can still climb effectively.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It is the most bipedal of all bears, and can walk upright for over 400 m (0.25 mi).
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The heel pads on the forefeet are larger than those of most other bear species.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Their claws, which are primarily used for climbing and digging, are slightly longer on the fore foot at 30–45 mm (1.2–1.8 in) than the back foot at 18–36 mm (0.71–1.42 in), and are larger and more hooked than those of the American black bear.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] On average, adult Asian black bears are slightly smaller than American black bears, though large males can exceed the size of several other bear species.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The famed British sportsman known as the "Old Shekarry" wrote of how an Asian black bear he shot in India probably weighed no less than 363 kg (800 lb) based on how many people it took to lift its body.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The largest Asian black bear on record allegedly weighed 200 kg (440 lb).
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Zoo-kept specimens can weigh up to 225 kg (496 lb).
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Although their senses are more acute than those of brown bears, their eyesight is poor, and their hearing range is moderate, the upper limit being 30 kHz.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] During the Middle Pleistocene and early Late Pleistocene, the Asian black bear ranged from the Iberian Peninsula, the Balkans to the Ural Mountains.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Today, it occurs very patchily in its former range from southeastern Iran eastward through Afghanistan and Pakistan, across the foothills of the Himalayas in India and Myanmar to mainland Southeast Asia, except Malaysia.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Its range in mainland China is patchy in the northeast and south, Hainan, and it is absent in much of east-central China.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Other population clusters exist in Taiwan, the southern Russian Far East and in North Korea.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Small remnant populations survive in South Korea, and on Honshu and Shikoku islands.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It typically inhabits deciduous forests, mixed forests and thornbrush forests.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In the summer, it usually inhabits elevations of around 3,500 m (11,480 ft) in the Himalayas but rarely above 3,700 m (12,000 ft).
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In winter, it descends to elevations below 1,500 m (4,920 ft).
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] There is no definitive estimate as to the number of Asian black bears: Japan posed estimates of 8–14,000 bears living on Honshū, though the reliability of this is now doubted.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Although their reliability is unclear, rangewide estimates of 5–6,000 Asian black bears have been presented by Russian biologists.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] According to the Mammal Society of Japan, the introduction of conservation policies by the Ministry of the Environment, along with a decline in hunters due to an aging population, has led to a significant increase in the population and expansion of the range of the Japanese black bear.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Estimates indicate that the population rose from approximately 15,000 individuals in 2012 to around 44,000 in 2023.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Rough density estimates without corroborating methodology or data have been made in India and Pakistan, resulting in the estimates of 7–9,000 in India and 1,000 in Pakistan.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Unsubstantiated estimates from China give varying estimates between 15 and 46,000, with a government estimate of 28,000.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Wildlife Trust of Bangladesh conducted an on-field survey of bears in Bangladesh from 2008 to 2010 that included Asian black bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The survey was done in 87 different places, mostly in the north-central, northeastern and southeastern areas of Bangladesh that had historical presence of bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The survey result says that most of the areas still has some isolated small bear populations, mainly the Asian black bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] According to the survey, the most evidence found relating to bears were of Asian black bears that included nests, footprints, local sightings, etc.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] There are many reports on the presence of Asian black bears in the central, north-central, northeastern and southeastern parts of Bangladesh.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Although Asian black bears still occur in different parts of Bangladesh, mainly in the Chittagong Hill Tracts, the population is very small.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Conservationists fear that the species will soon be extinct in the country if necessary steps to protect it are not taken in the near future.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Three subspecies of the Asian black bear occur in China: the Tibetan subspecies (*U. thibetanus thibetanus*), the Indochinese subspecies (*U. thibetanus mupinensis*), and the northeastern subspecies (*U. thibetanus ussuricus*), which is the only subspecies of bear in northeastern China.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears are mainly distributed in the conifer forests in the cold and temperate zones of northeast China, the main areas being Changbai, Zhang Guangcai, Lao Ye, and the Lesser Xingan Mountains.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Within Liaoning province, there are about 100 Asian black bears, which only inhabit the five counties of Xinbin, Huanren, Benxi, Kuandian, and Fencheng.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Within Jilin province, Asian black bears occur mainly in the counties of Hunchun, Dunhua, Wangqing, Antu, Changbai, Fusong, Jiaohe, Huadian, Panshi, and Shulan.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In Heilongjiang province, Asian black bears occur in the counties of Ningan, Bayan, Wuchang, Tonghe, Baoqing, Fuyuan, Yichun, Taoshan, Lanxi, Tieli, Sunwu, Aihui, Dedu, Beian, and Nenjiang.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] This population has a northern boundary of about 50° N and the southern boundary in Fengcheng is about 40°30" N.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] By the 1990s, poaching, habitat destruction, and eradication during the Japanese occupation had led to the local extinction of the species from South Korea.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In 2004, the South Korean government initiated a reintroduction program in Jiri Mountain National Park.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The effort has been successful, with bears now inhabiting the park and dispersing into northern forests.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In 2021, the park's bear population appeared to have reached its carrying capacity.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In Korea, most of the Asian black bears live in the broad-leaved forest of the alpine region, more than 1,500 meters north of Jirisan.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] As of April 2018, there were 56 bears living in the wild of Jirisan.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] However, since then, many of these areas have not been revisited to confirm its presence, particularly in the southern districts of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, Balochistan and Sindh.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Baluchistan black bear occurs throughout the mountainous Balochistan region in western Pakistan, south-eastern Iran and south-western Afghanistan.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Baluchistan black bear is now limited in southwestern Pakistan and southeast Iran.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In Siberia, the Asian black bear's northern range runs from Innokenti Bay on the coast of the Sea of Japan southwest to the elevated areas of Sikhote Alin crossing it at the sources of the Samarga River.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] At this point, the boundary directs itself to the north, through the middle course of the Khor, Anyui and Khungari rivers, and comes to the shore of the Amur, crossing it at the level of the mouth of the Gorin River.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Along the Amur river, the species' presence has been noted as far as 51° N.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] From there, the territorial boundary runs southwest of the river's left bank, passing through the northern part of Lake Bolon and the juncture point of the Kur and Tunguska.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears are encountered in the Urmi's lower course.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Within the Ussuri krai, the species is restricted to broad-leaved Manchurian-type forests.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In Taiwan, the endemic subspecies of Asian black bear, the Formosan black bear (*Ursus thibetanus formosanus*), is confined to the mountain ranges in the central regions of the island.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It lives along the Central and Snow Mountain Range, with populations in the latter being more common.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The largest population seems to live in Lala mountain in Chatienshan Reserve, the (Snow) Mountain area in Shei-Pa National Park and Taroko National Park south to Tawushan Reserve through Yushan National Park.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] This population is estimated to comprise 200 to 600 individuals.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears are diurnal, though they become nocturnal near human habitations.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] They will walk in a procession of largest to smallest.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] They are good climbers of rocks and trees, and will climb to feed, rest, sun, elude enemies and hibernate.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Some older bears may become too heavy to climb.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Half of their life is spent in trees and they are one of the largest arboreal mammals.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In the Ussuri territory in the Russian Far East, Asian black bears can spend up to 15% of their time in trees.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears break branches and twigs to place under themselves when feeding on trees, thus causing many trees in their home ranges to have nest-like structures on their tops.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears will rest for short periods in nests on trees standing fifteen feet or higher.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears do not hibernate over most of their range.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] They may hibernate in their colder, northern ranges, though some bears will simply move to lower elevations.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears prepare their dens for hibernation in mid-October, and will sleep from November until March.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Their dens can either be dug-out hollow trees (60 feet above ground), caves or holes in the ground, hollow logs, or steep, mountainous and sunny slopes.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] They may also den in abandoned brown bear dens.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears tend to den at lower elevations and on less steep slopes than brown bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Female Asian black bears emerge from dens later than do males, and female Asian black bears with cubs emerge later than barren females.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears tend to be less mobile than brown bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] With sufficient food, Asian black bears can remain in an area of roughly 1–2 km2 (0.39–0.77 sq mi), and sometimes even as little as 0.5–1 km2 (0.19–0.39 sq mi).
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears have a wide range of vocalizations, including grunts, whines, roars, slurping sounds (sometimes made when feeding) and "an appalling row" when wounded, alarmed or angry.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] They emit loud hisses when issuing warnings or threats, and scream when fighting.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] When approaching other bears, they produce "tut tut" sounds, thought to be produced by bears snapping their tongue against the roof of their mouth.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] When courting, they emit clucking sounds.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Within Sikhote-Alin, the breeding season of Asian black bears occurs earlier than in brown bears, starting from mid-June to mid-August.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Birth also occurs earlier, in mid-January.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] By October, the uterine horns of pregnant females grow to 15–22 mm (0.59–0.87 in).
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] By late December, the embryos weigh 75 grams.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Sows generally have their first litter at the age of three years.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Pregnant females generally make up 14% of populations.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Similar to brown bears, Asian black bears have delayed implantation.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Sows usually give birth in caves or hollow trees in winter or early spring after a gestation period of 200–240 days.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Cubs weigh 13 ounces at birth, and will begin walking at four days of age, and open their eyes three days later.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The skulls of newborn Asian black bear cubs bear great resemblance to those of adult sun bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Litters can consist of 1–4 cubs, with 2 being the average.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Cubs have a slow growth rate, reaching only 2.5 kg by May.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bear cubs will nurse for 104–130 weeks, and become independent at 24–36 months.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] There is usually a 2–3 year interval period before females produce subsequent litters.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The average lifespan in the wild is 25 years, while the oldest Asian black bear in captivity died at the age of 44.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Asian black bear is omnivorous and feeds on insects, beetle larvae, invertebrates, termites, grubs, carrion, bees, eggs, garbage, mushrooms, grasses, bark, roots, tubers, fruits, nuts, seeds, honey, herbs, acorns, cherries, dogwood and grain.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It eats pine nuts and acorns of the previous year in the April–May period.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In times of scarcity, it enters river valleys to gain access to hazelnuts and insect larvae in rotting logs.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] From mid-May through late June, it supplement its diet with green vegetation and fruit.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Through July to September, it climbs trees to eat bird cherries, pine cones, vines and grapes.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] On rare occasions, it eats dead fish during the spawning season, though this constitutes a much lesser portion of its diet.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In the 1970s, Asian black bears were reported to kill and eat Hanuman langurs in Nepal.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It also kills ungulates with some regularity, including domestic livestock.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Wild ungulate prey can include muntjacs, serow, takin, Malayan tapir wild boar and adult water buffaloes, which it kills by breaking their necks.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Black bears in Japan, specifically, are reported as mainly eating acorns throughout the year and having similar caloric fluctuations.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Their energy balance declines from May to June, rises again in August through October, and declines once more in November.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Male and female bears both have a higher energy balance in good mast years rather than poor mast years.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Moreover, during a poor mast year, male bears' energy intake will become negative in February during their hibernation period, and will not exceed zero until August, even if they can begin feeding earlier in the year.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Asian black bear's range overlaps with that of the sloth bear in central and southern India, the sun bear in Southeast Asia and the brown bear in the southern part of the Russian Far East.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears seem to intimidate Himalayan brown bears in direct encounters.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] They eat the fruit dropped by Asian black bears from trees, as they themselves are too large and cumbersome to climb.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Ussuri brown bears may attack Asian black bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears are occasionally attacked by tigers and brown bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Leopards are known to prey on bear cubs younger than two years old.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Packs of wolves and Eurasian lynxes are potential predators of bear cubs as well.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears usually dominate Amur leopards in physical confrontations in heavily vegetated areas, while leopards are uppermost in open areas, though the outcome of such encounters is largely dependent on the size of the individual animals.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Tigers occasionally attack and consume Asian black bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Russian hunters found their remains in tiger scats, and Asian black bear carcasses showing evidence of tiger predation.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] To escape tigers, Asian black bears rush up a tree and wait for the tiger to leave, though some tigers will pretend to leave, and wait for the bear to descend.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Some are very tenacious when attacked: Jim Corbett observed a fight between a tiger and the largest Asian black bear he had ever seen.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The bear managed to chase off the tiger, despite having half its nose and scalp torn off.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] He twice saw Asian black bears carry off tiger kills when the latter was absent.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears are usually safe from tiger attacks once they reach five years of age.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] One fatal attack of a tiger on a juvenile Asian black bear has been recorded in Jigme Dorji National Park.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] One Siberian tiger was reported to have lured an Asian black bear by imitating its mating call.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] However, Asian black bears are probably less vulnerable to tiger attacks than brown bears, due to their habit of living in hollows or in close set rocks.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Asian black bear is listed as a protected animal in China's National Protection Wildlife Law, which stipulates that anyone hunting or catching bears without permits will be subject to severe punishment.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Moreover, due to India's wide-stretching boundaries with other nations such as Pakistan, Tibet, China, Nepal, Bhutan, Bangladesh and Myanmar, it is difficult to police such borders, which are often in mountainous terrain.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Five Asian black bear populations, occurring in Kyushu, Shikoku, West-Chugoku, East-Chugoku and Kii areas, were listed as endangered by the Environmental Agency in the Japanese Red Data Book in 1991.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Small isolated populations in the Tanzawa and Shimokita areas of mainland Honshū were listed as endangered in 1995.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In 2000, the Ministry of the Environment introduced a bear management manual that set an upper limit on the annual capture rate relative to the estimated population, marking a full shift toward conservation policy.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The manual has since undergone several revisions.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] As hunting quotas declined and as the number of hunters decreased due to an aging population, the Japanese black bear population grew rapidly through 2023, particularly on Honshu.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears occur as an infrequent species in the Red Data Book of Russia, thus falling under special protection and hunting is prohibited.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] There is currently a strong movement to legalize the hunting of Russian black bears, which is supported by most of the local scientific community.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] As of January 30, 1989, Taiwan's Formosan black bears have been listed as an endangered species under the Natural and Cultural Heritage Act on, and was later listed as a Conserved Species Category I.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Vietnamese government issued Decision 276/QD, 276/1989, which prohibits the hunting and exporting of Asian black bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Red Book of Vietnam lists Vietnamese black bears as endangered.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Korean Government designated the Asian black bear as Natural Monument No.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] 329 and it is considered an extinction crisis.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] At the present time, the Endangered Species Restoration Center of Korea National Park Service is going through species restoration business.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Asiatic black bear and the subspecies Baluchistan black bear have been classified as vulnerable since 1979 and critically endangered since 1996 in Pakistan, respectively, on the IUCN Red List.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Additionally, they are both listed in Appendix I of the Convention on the International Trade of Endangered Species.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The main habitat threat to Asian black bears is overcutting of forests, mainly due to human populations increasing to over 430,000 in regions where bears are distributed, in the Shaanxi, Ganshu, and Sichuan provinces.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] 27 forestry enterprises were built in these areas between 1950 and 1985 (excluding the lumbering units belonging to the county).
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] By the early 1990s, the Asian black bear distribution area was reduced to only one-fifth of the area that existed before the 1940s.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Isolated bear populations face environmental and genetic stress in these circumstances.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] However, one of the most important reasons for their decrease involves overhunting, as Asian black bear paws, gall bladders and cubs have great economic value.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bear harvests are maintained at a high level due to the harm they cause to crops, orchards and bee farms.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] During the 1950s and 1960s, 1,000 Asian black bears were harvested annually in the Heilongjiang Province.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] However, purchased furs were reduced by 4/5, even by 9/10 yearly in the late 1970s to the early 1980s.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears have also been declining annually in Dehong Dai and Jingpo Autonomous Prefecture and Yunnan.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Poaching for gall bladders and skin are the main threats faced by Asian black bears in India.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In Pakistan, in addition to direct killing, commercial poaching, and human-bear conflict, the primary concerns are habitat loss brought on by logging, the growth of plantations and agriculture, road networks, and dams.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] From 11,807 km² in the 1950s to 7,925 km² in 2014, the Asiatic black bear population has decreased.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It primarily inhabits lower-altitude areas of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, Gilgit-Baltistan, and Azad Jammu and Kashmir, which are distinguished by densely populated areas, forested vegetation, and related agriculture.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] From the 1970s to the 1980s, Japan conducted large-scale culling of black bears in spring to prevent bark stripping of cedar and cypress plantations, which led to a sharp decline in their population.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In response, from the late 1980s, hunting restrictions and voluntary self-restraint were introduced in western Japan, reducing the number of bears hunted, although poaching remained a problem.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In 2000, the Ministry of the Environment established a management manual aimed at population recovery, explicitly setting annual culling limits based on estimated population size; this manual was subsequently revised several times.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Following this, hunting numbers declined due to both conservation policies and the aging hunter population, allowing the bear population to recover.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Combined with poor mast production caused by climate change, this population recovery contributed to a sharp increase in injuries and fatalities caused by bears around 2023, reaching a record high in 2025.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Consequently, in 2024, the Japanese government revised the existing black bear conservation plan, shifting toward a more proactive population management policy through hunting, with many bears again becoming targets for culling.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Although Asian black bears have been afforded protection in Russia since 1983, illegal poaching, fueled by a growing demand for bear parts in the Asian market, is still a major threat to the Russian population.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Many workers of Chinese and Korean origin, supposedly employed in the timber industry, are actually involved in the illegal trade.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Some Russian sailors reportedly purchase bear parts from local hunters to sell them to Japanese and Southeast Asian clients.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Russia's rapidly growing timber industry has been a serious threat to the Asian black bear's home range for three decades.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The cutting of trees containing cavities deprives Asian black bears of their main source of dens, and forces them to den on the ground or in rocks, thus making them more vulnerable to tigers, brown bears and hunters.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In Taiwan, Asian black bears are not actively pursued, though steel traps set out for wild boars have been responsible for unintentional bear trappings.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The building of new cross island highways through bear habitat is also potentially threatening.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Vietnamese black bear populations have declined rapidly due to the pressures of human population growth and unstable settlement.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Vietnamese forests have been shrinking: of the 87,000 km2 (34,000 sq mi) of natural forests, about 1,000 km2 (390 sq mi) disappear every year.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Hunting pressures have also increased with a coinciding decline of environmental awareness.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] South Korea remains one of two countries to allow bear bile farming to continue legally.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] As reported in 2009, approximately 1,374 Asian black bears reside in an estimated 74 bear farms, where they are kept for slaughter to fuel the demands of traditional Asian medicine.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In sharp contrast, fewer than 20 Asian black bears can be found at Jirisan Restoration Center, located in Korea's Jirisan National Park.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In recent years, climate change has also contributed to the declining Asian black bear population across southern and southeastern Iran.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] As large mammals, these bears respond more to climate change than small prey species.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Due to their large size, Asian black bears are unable to utilize micro-climatic refuges, like hiding in grass to regulate temperature.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Over the past thirty years, a thirty to forty percent decrease has been reported in the Asian black bear population, correlating with the rise in global temperatures.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Along with that, a ten percent decrease in suitable habitat has been reported since 2016, due to climate change and deforestation.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In Japanese culture, the Asian black bear is traditionally associated with the mountain spirit (*yama no kami*) and is characterized variously as 'mountain man' (**yamaotoko**), 'mountain uncle' (*yama no ossan*), 'mountain father' (*yama no oyaji*), a loving mother, and a child.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Being a largely solitary creature, the Asian black bear is also viewed as 'lonely person' (*sabishigariya*).
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bears feature very little in lowland Japanese folklore, but are prominent in upland Japan, a fact thought to reflect the bear's greater economic value in upland areas.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] According to the local folklore in Kituarahara-gun in Niigata, the Asian black bear received its white mark after being given a silk-wrapped amulet by *yama no kami*, which left the mark after being removed.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In Hindu mythology, the Asian black bear Jambavantha (also known as Jambavan or Jamvanta) is believed to have lived from Treta Yuga to Dvapara Yuga.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the epic *Ramayana*, Jambavantha assists Rama in finding his wife Sita and battle her abductor, Ravana.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The Asian black bear in Thailand is called *mi khwai* (Thai: หมีควาย), meaning 'buffalo bear', not due to its appearance, but a v-shaped patch of fur under its neck similar to that of a buffalo.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] There is also a Thai idiom, *bon meuan mi kin pheung* (Thai: บ่นเหมือนหมีกินผึ้ง), literally 'grumbling like a bear eating honey', referring to people who display behaviors of grumbling and mumbling to express dissatisfaction.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] This idiom comes from the behavior of this species of bear when it climbs trees in search of honey and young bees.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] While eating honey, it makes a murmuring sound.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In Taiwan, the Bunun people regard bears and humans as sharing common ancestry.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The Formosan black bear emerged as a symbol of Taiwanese nationalism in the 21st century, often in contradistinction or shown in conflict with the panda (as a symbol of the PRC), or with Winnie-the-Pooh (as a symbol of Xi Jinping).
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bears are briefly mentioned in Yann Martel's novel *The Life of Pi*, in which they are described by the protagonist's father as being among the most dangerous animals in his zoo.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Historically, one of the main threats to the Asiatic black bear populations in Pakistan was the capture of cubs to use in bear dancing and baiting for entertainment in streets and villages, especially for tourists.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Although usually shy and cautious animals, Asian black bears are more aggressive towards humans than the brown bears of Eurasia and American black bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Macdonald theorizes that this greater aggression is an adaptation to being sympatric with tigers.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] At the turn of the 20th century, a hospital in Srinagar, Kashmir received dozens of Asian black bear victims annually.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] When Asian black bears attack humans, they rear up on their hind legs and knock victims over with their front paws.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Then they bite them on an arm or leg and snap on the victim's head, this being the most dangerous part of the attack.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bear attacks have been increasing in Kashmir since the Kashmir conflict.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In November 2009, in the Kulgam district of Indian-administered Kashmir, an Asian black bear attacked four insurgents after discovering them in its den, and killed two of them.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In India, attacks on humans have been increasing yearly, and have occurred largely in the northwestern and western Himalayan region.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the Chamba District of Himachal Pradesh, the number of Asian black bear attacks on humans has gradually increased from 10 in 1988–89 to 21 in 1991–92.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] There are no records of predation on humans by Asian black bears in Russia, and no conflicts have been documented in Taiwan.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bear attacks on humans were reported from Junbesi in Langtang National Park, Nepal in 2005, and occurred in villages as well as in the surrounding forest.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Nine people were killed by Asian black bears in Japan between 1979 and 1989.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In September 2009, an Asian black bear attacked a group of 9 tourists, seriously injuring four of them at a bus station in the built-up area of Takayama, Gifu.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The majority of attacks tend to occur when Asian black bears are encountered suddenly, and in close quarters.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Because of this, Asian black bears are generally considered more dangerous than brown bears, which live in more open spaces and are thus less likely to be surprised by approaching humans.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] They are also likely to attack when protecting food.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] 2016 saw several attacks by Asian black bears in Japan.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In May and June four people were killed by Asian black bears in Akita prefecture while picking bamboo shoots, and in August a female safari park worker in Gunma prefecture was killed when an Asian black bear climbed into her car and attacked her.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] According to a recent review, humans killed ca.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] 50/100 individuals of the Himalayan black bear between 1998 and 2023 in Pakistan.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] No data were reported for the Baluchistan black bear.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] However, we are well aware that this value is greatly underestimated because this type of information is often intentionally concealed.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the past, the farmers of the Himalayan lowlands feared Asian black bears more than any other pest, and would erect platforms in the fields, where watchmen would be posted at night and would beat drums to frighten off any interlopers.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] However, some Asian black bears would grow accustomed to the sound and encroach anyway.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Of 1,375 livestock kills examined in Bhutan, Asian black bears accounted for 8% of attacks.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Livestock predation, overall, was greatest in the summer and autumn periods, which corresponded with a peak in cropping agriculture; livestock are turned out to pasture and forest during the cropping season and, subsequently, are less well-guarded than at other times.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Livestock killed by Asian black bears in Himachal Pradesh, India increased from 29 in 1988–1989 to 45 in 1992–1993.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the remoter areas of Japan, Asian black bears can be serious crop predators: the bears feed on cultivated bamboo shoots in spring, on plums, watermelons and corn in the summer, and on persimmons, sweet potatoes and rice in the autumn.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Japanese black bears are estimated to damage 3,000 bee hives annually.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] When feeding on large crops such as watermelons or pumpkins, Asian black bears will ignore the flesh and eat the seeds, thus adversely affecting future harvests.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bears can girdle and kill trees by stripping their bark for the sap.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] This can cause serious economic problems in Asia's valuable timber forests.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the late 1970s, 400–1,200 hectares (990–2,970 acres) of land had been affected by Asian black bears bark-stripping Japanese conifers.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] There is evidence that 70-year-old conifers (commanding the highest market values) may also have been bark-stripped.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bears will prey on livestock if their natural food is in poor supply.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] They have been known to attack bullocks, either killing them outright, or eating them alive.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Along with sun bears, Asian black bears are the most typically used species in areas where bears are used either in performances or as pets.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bears have an outstanding learning ability in captivity, and are among the most common species used in circus acts.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bears are easily tamed, and can be fed with rice, maize, sweet potatoes, cassavas, pumpkins, ripe fruit, animal fat and sweet foods.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Keeping captive Asian black bears is popular in China, especially due to the belief that milking the bear's gall bladder leads to quick prosperity.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bears are also popular as pets in Vietnam.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] — *The Great and Small Game of India, Burma, and Tibet* p.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The book also describes a second method of black bear hunting involving the beating of small patches of forest, when the bears march out in single file.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] However, black bears were rarely hunted for sport, because of the poor quality of their fur and the ease by which they could be shot in trees, or stalked, as their hearing was poor.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Although easy to track and shoot, Asian black bears were known by British sportsmen to be extremely dangerous when injured.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Burton wrote of how many sportsmen had been killed by Asian black bears after failing to make direct hits.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Today, Asian black bears are only legally hunted for sport in Japan and Russia.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In Russia, 75–100 Asian black bears are legally harvested annually, though 500 a year are reportedly harvested illegally.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] After the introduction of Buddhism in Japan, which prohibited the killing of animals, the Japanese compromised by devising different strategies in hunting bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Some, such as the inhabitants of the Kiso area in the Nagano Prefecture, prohibited the practice altogether, while others developed rituals in order to placate the spirits of killed bears.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In some Japanese hunting communities, Asian black bears lacking the white chest mark are considered sacred.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the Akita Prefecture, bears lacking the mark were known by *matagi* huntsmen as *minaguro* ('all-black') or *munaguro* ('black-chested'), and were also considered messengers of **yama no kami**.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] If such a bear was shot, the huntsman would offer it to **yama no kami**, and give up hunting from that time on.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Similar beliefs were held in Nagano, where the completely black Asian black bears were termed *nekoguma*, 'cat-bear'.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] *Matagi* communities believed that killing an Asian black bear in the mountains would result in a bad storm, which was linked to the belief that bear spirits could affect weather.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The *matagi* would generally hunt Asian black bears in spring or from late autumn to early winter, before they hibernated.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In mountain regions, Asian black bears were hunted by driving them upland to a waiting hunter, who would then shoot it.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Bear hunting expeditions were preceded by rituals, and could last up to two weeks.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] After killing the bear, the *matagi* would pray for the bear's soul.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bear hunts in Japan are often termed *kuma taiji*, meaning 'bear conquest'.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The word *taiji* itself is often used in Japanese folklore to describe the slaying of monsters and demons.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Traditionally, the Atayal, Taroko, and Bunun people of Taiwan consider Asian black bears to be almost human in their behaviors, and thus unjust killing of bears is equated with murder and will cause misfortunes such as disease, death, or crop failure.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The Bunun people call Asian black bears *aguman* or *duman*, which means 'devil'.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Traditionally, a Bunun hunter who has accidentally trapped an Asian black bear has to build a cottage in the mountains and cremate the bear within it.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The hunter must stay in the cottage alone, away from the village until the end of the millet harvest, as it is believed that the killing of an Asian black bear will cause the millet crop to burn black.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the Tungpu area, Asian black bears are considered animals of the "third category": animals with the most remote relationship to humans and whose activity is restricted outside human settlements.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Therefore, when Asian black bears encroach upon human settlements, they are considered ill omens.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In this situation, the community can either destroy the trespassing bears or settle somewhere else.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The Rukai and Paiwan people are permitted to hunt Asian black bears, though they believe that doing so will curse the hunters involved: Rukai people believe that hunting Asian black bears can result in disease.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Children are forbidden from eating bear meat, which is itself not permitted to be taken within homes.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bears have been hunted for their body parts in China since the Stone Age.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the 19th century, its fur was considered of low value.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Grease was the only practical use for their carcasses in British India, and bears living near villages were considered ideal, as they were almost invariably fatter than forest-dwelling ones.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the former USSR, the Asian black bear yielded fur, meat and fat of greater quality than those of the brown bear.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Today, bile is in demand, as it supposedly cures various diseases, treats the accumulation of blood below the skin, and counters toxic effects.
[src:bear-conservation/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Products also include bone 'glue' and fat, both used in traditional medicine and consumed as a tonic.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] The most effective way to implement ANR is very site-specific, and many nations provide guidebooks on how to select and maintain an ANR project.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR is a common practice in many Asian countries.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] This method of protection has been used on *Imperata* grasslands in the Philippines for over three decades, as well as in China for more than five decades.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] According to the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO), China has since 1999 funded extensive ANR in an effort to prevent soil corrosion in particular.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] Also the FAO reports that ANR is a common practice in Thailand.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR is gaining popularity as global climate change becomes a growing concern.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR has typically been used most often in tropical forests, however, it is now being used to help restore forested areas across all ecosystem types.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] A wide variety of conditions are required to optimally implement ANR and ensure successful regeneration.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] One involves a sufficient density of naturally regenerated seedlings, though the specific density required is dependent on specific factors, such as, distribution, species composition, growth rates, soil fertility, etc.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] A density range of 200 to 800 seedlings per hectare has been suggested to ensure optimal regeneration.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] The availability of seed sources from nearby remnant forests is necessary to serve as seed inputs for colonization of vegetation.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] The control or removal of all disturbances (such as, grazing, fires, and logging) is also crucial.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] The practice of ANR has a wide range of benefits.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR focuses on reducing ecological barriers in order to accelerate natural regeneration and growth, rather than the planting of seedlings.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] This allows for a low-cost method that removes the expenses associated with site preparation and planting/raising seedlings themselves, which can be appealing in large-scale restoration projects.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] Another benefit involves job opportunities.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR requires high maintenance and can be labor-intensive, and involve methods of weeding, grass pressing, establishing and maintaining firebreaks, etc.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] This can ultimately help to create jobs and improve livelihoods in local and/or impoverished communities.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] However, if the forestation is not a positive change, for example, if the land is needed for food, the people of the community will be unlikely to get involved and produce successful ANR.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] Carbon sequestration, biodiversity enrichment and recovery are just a few environmental benefits ANR provides, which can help improve ecosystems and mitigate climate change.
[src:bear-conservation/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR focuses on native species and natural succession of existing vegetation, which ensures that plant communities and inhabiting wildlife are maintained and are not disturbed.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] Bears face serious threats on many fronts, most of which are due to human activity.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] Whether indirect, as in human encroachment on their natural habitats due to crop cultivation, deforestation or timber harvest, or directly from their killing for protection of property or for unregulated or sport hunting, or for their use in primitive medicines and aphrodisiacs.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] In a paper presented at the International Bear Association’s Eighth International Conference on Bear Research and Management, Victoria, British Columbia, Canada, in 1989, Christopher Servheen, of the U.S.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] According to Servheen, bear conservation efforts vary from the intensive and highly organized management of the grizzly bear in the United States to little management in Asian countries.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] However, since 2004 the non-profit organization Free the Bears (FTB) has been working to rescue bears in Asia along with educating the local communities.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] They help combat the illegal wildlife trade of bears and often transport the rescues to world-class sanctuaries.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] This dedicated program is not only working to reduce illegal trade and capture of bears in the Asian area but other impoverished and dangerous parts of the world.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] Likewise, successful international co-operation in conservation and management is exemplified by the work done on the polar bear in the Arctic.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] Several other species also need international cooperation to if they are to survive.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] However, even species of "least concern" such as the brown bear are at risk of extirpation in certain countries or regions beyond their range in North America, parts of Europe, and the former Soviet Union.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] The process of decline and/or extinction of the brown bear in Europe is well documented.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] Starting with their extinction in Denmark around 3000 BC, in Great Britain during the 10th century, in eastern Germany in 1770, in Bavaria in 1836, in Switzerland in 1904, and in the French Alps in 1937.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] Although the inclusion of the brown bear as of least concern on the 2006 IUCN Red List of Threatened Species refers to their global population, the fact is that local populations are increasingly becoming scarcer.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] Such regional variations are most obvious in Spain where the only remaining bear, the Cantabrian brown bear is under threat.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] Spain’s ministry of the environment, in its *Catálogo Nacional de Especies Amenazadas* lists the brown bear as in danger of extinction in Spain.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] According to an article published December 2007 in the Spanish national daily *El País*, eight brown bears had been killed, either by poisoned bait or illegal hunting, in the Cantabrian Mountains since 2000.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] The Cantabrian brown bear population is currently (2007) estimated at around 170, divided between the 140 in the western section and 25-30 in the eastern.
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] Leading Spanish experts have warned that the bear population will not be viable until there are "several hundred".
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] One way forward is to reverse the fragmentation of the bears' habitat by creating "corridors".
[src:bear-conservation/bear-conservation] However, their viability is compromised by the regional authorities' keenness to allow construction of a ski resort at San Glorio, a project which has met strong opposition from many sectors, as well as that of the central government.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] While the polar bear is mostly carnivorous, and the giant panda is mostly herbivorous, the remaining six species are omnivorous with varying diets.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] With the exception of courting individuals and mothers with their young, bears are typically solitary animals.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] They may be diurnal or nocturnal, and they have an excellent sense of smell.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Despite their heavy build and awkward gait, they are adept runners, climbers, and swimmers.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears use shelters, such as caves and logs, as their dens; most species occupy their dens during the winter for a long period of hibernation, up to 100 days.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears have been hunted since prehistoric times for their meat and fur.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] They have also been used for bear-baiting and other forms of entertainment, such as being made to dance.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] With their powerful physical presence, they play a prominent role in the arts, mythology, and other cultural aspects of various human societies.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] In modern times, bears have come under pressure through encroachment on their habitats and illegal trade in bear parts, including the Asian bile bear market.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The IUCN lists six bear species as vulnerable or endangered, and even least concern species, such as the brown bear, are at risk of extirpation in certain countries.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The poaching and international trade of these most threatened populations are prohibited, but still ongoing.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The English word "bear" comes from Old English **bera** and belongs to a family of names for the bear in Germanic languages, such as Swedish **björn**, also used as a first name.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] This form is conventionally said to be related to a Proto-Indo-European word for "brown", so that "bear" would mean "the brown one".
[src:bear-conservation/bear] However, Ringe notes that while this etymology is semantically plausible, a word meaning "brown" of this form cannot be found in Proto-Indo-European.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] He suggests instead that "bear" is from the Proto-Indo-European word **ǵʰwḗr- ~ *ǵʰwér* "wild animal".
[src:bear-conservation/bear] This terminology for the animal originated as a taboo avoidance term: proto-Germanic tribes replaced their original word for bear—*arkto*—with this euphemistic expression out of fear that speaking the animal's true name might cause it to appear.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] According to author Ralph Keyes, this is the oldest known euphemism.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bear taxon names such as Arctoidea and *Helarctos* come from the ancient Greek ἄρκτος (*arktos*), meaning bear, as do the names "arctic" and "antarctic", via the name of the constellation Ursa Major, the "Great Bear", prominent in the northern sky.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bear taxon names such as Ursidae and *Ursus* come from Latin *Ursus/Ursa*, he-bear/she-bear.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The female first name "Ursula", originally derived from a Christian saint's name, means "little she-bear" (diminutive of Latin *ursa*).
[src:bear-conservation/bear] In Switzerland, the male first name "Urs" is especially popular, while the name of the canton and city of Bern is by legend derived from *Bär*, German for bear.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The Germanic name Bernard (including Bernhardt and similar forms) means "bear-brave", "bear-hardy", or "bold bear".
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The Old English name Beowulf is a kenning, "bee-wolf", for bear, in turn meaning a brave warrior.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The earliest members of Ursidae belong to the extinct subfamily Amphicynodontinae, including *Parictis* (late Eocene to early middle Miocene, 38–18 Mya) and the slightly younger *Allocyon* (early Oligocene, 34–30 Mya), both from North America.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] These animals looked very different from today's bears, being small and raccoon-like in overall appearance, with diets perhaps more similar to that of a badger.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] It is unclear whether late-Eocene ursids were also present in Eurasia, although faunal exchange across the Bering land bridge may have been possible during a major sea level low stand as early as the late Eocene (about 37 Mya) and continuing into the early Oligocene.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] European genera morphologically very similar to *Allocyon*, and to the much younger American *Kolponomos* (about 18 Mya), are known from the Oligocene, including *Amphicticeps* and *Amphicynodon*.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] There has been various morphological evidence linking amphicynodontines with pinnipeds, as both groups were semi-aquatic, otter-like mammals.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] In addition to the support of the pinniped–amphicynodontine clade, other morphological and some molecular evidence supports bears being the closest living relatives to pinnipeds.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The raccoon-sized, dog-like *Cephalogale* is the oldest-known member of the subfamily Hemicyoninae, which first appeared during the middle Oligocene in Eurasia about 30 Mya.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The subfamily includes the younger genera *Phoberocyon* (20–15 Mya), and *Plithocyon* (15–7 Mya).
[src:bear-conservation/bear] A *Cephalogale*-like species gave rise to the genus *Ursavus* during the early Oligocene (30–28 Mya); this genus proliferated into many species in Asia and is ancestral to all living bears.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Species of *Ursavus* subsequently entered North America, together with *Amphicynodon* and *Cephalogale*, during the early Miocene (21–18 Mya).
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Members of the living lineages of bears diverged from *Ursavus* between 15 and 20 Mya, likely via the species *Ursavus elmensis*.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Based on genetic and morphological data, the Ailuropodinae (pandas) were the first to diverge from other living bears about 19 Mya, although no fossils of this group have been found before about 11 Mya.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The New World short-faced bears (Tremarctinae) differentiated from Ursinae following a dispersal event into North America during the mid-Miocene (about 13 Mya).
[src:bear-conservation/bear] They invaded South America (≈2.5 or 1.2 Ma) following formation of the Isthmus of Panama.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Their earliest fossil representative is *Plionarctos* in North America (c.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Ursids did not diversify as much when colonising South America as they did when colonising the Holarctic, however.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The subfamily Ursinae experienced a dramatic proliferation of taxa about 5.3–4.5 Mya, coincident with major environmental changes; the first members of the genus *Ursus* appeared around this time.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The sloth bear is a modern survivor of one of the earliest lineages to diverge during this radiation event (5.3 Mya); it took on its peculiar morphology, related to its diet of termites and ants, no later than by the early Pleistocene.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] By 3–4 Mya, the species *Ursus minimus* appears in the fossil record of Europe; apart from its size, it was nearly identical to today's Asian black bear.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] It is likely ancestral to all bears within Ursinae, perhaps aside from the sloth bear.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Two lineages evolved from *U. minimus*: the black bears (including the sun bear, the Asian black bear, and the American black bear); and the brown bears (which includes the polar bear).
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Modern brown bears evolved from *U. minimus* via *Ursus etruscus*, which itself is ancestral to the extinct Pleistocene cave bear.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Species of Ursinae have migrated repeatedly into North America from Eurasia as early as 4 Mya during the early Pliocene.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The polar bear is the most recently evolved species and descended from a population of brown bears that became isolated in northern latitudes by glaciation 400,000 years ago.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The relationship of the bear family with other carnivorans is shown in the following phylogenetic tree, which is based on the molecular phylogenetic analysis of six genes in Flynn (2005) with the musteloids updated following the multigene analysis of Law et al.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Note that although they are called "bears" in some languages, red pandas and raccoons and their close relatives are not bears, but rather musteloids.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] One possible phylogeny is based on complete mitochondrial DNA sequences from Yu et al.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The polar bear and the brown bear form a close grouping, while the relationships of the other species are not very well resolved.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] A more recent phylogeny is based on the genetic study of Kumar et al.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] It concludes that Ursine bears originated around five million years ago, with extensive hybridization among the different species.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] McLellan and colleagues (1992) classified the bears into seven subfamilies: Amphicynodontinae, Hemicyoninae, Ursavinae, Agriotheriinae, Ailuropodinae, Tremarctinae, and Ursinae.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] (1997) instead classified the bear species into the superfamily **Ursoidea**, with Hemicyoninae and Agriotheriinae being classified in the family "Hemicyonidae".
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Amphicynodontinae under this classification were classified as stem-pinnipeds in the superfamily Phocoidea.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] In the McKenna and Bell classification, both bears and pinnipeds are in a parvorder of carnivoran mammals known as Ursida, along with the extinct bear dogs of the family Amphicyonidae.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Wesley-Hunt and Flynn (2005) classify the Ursidae as one of nine families in the suborder Caniformia, within the order Carnivora.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Modern bears comprise eight species in three subfamilies: Ailuropodinae (monotypic with the giant panda), Tremarctinae (monotypic with the spectacled bear), and Ursinae (containing six species divided into one to three genera, depending on the authority).
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Nuclear chromosome analysis show that the karyotype of the six ursine bears is nearly identical, each having 74 chromosomes (*see* Ursid hybrid), whereas the giant panda has 42 chromosomes and the spectacled bear 52.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The bear family includes the most massive extant terrestrial members of the order Carnivora.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The polar bear is considered to be the largest extant species, with adult males weighing 350–700 kg (770–1,540 lb) and measuring 2.4–3 m (7 ft 10 in – 9 ft 10 in) in total length.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The smallest species is the sun bear, which ranges 25–65 kg (55–143 lb) in weight and 100–140 cm (39–55 in) in length.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Prehistoric North and South American short-faced bears were the largest species known to have lived.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The latter estimated to have weighed 1,600 kg (3,500 lb) and stood 3.4 m (11 ft) tall.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Body weight varies throughout the year in bears of temperate and arctic climates, as they build up fat reserves in the summer and autumn and lose weight during the winter.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears are generally bulky and robust animals with short tails.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] They are sexually dimorphic with regard to size, with males typically being larger.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Larger species tend to show increased levels of sexual dimorphism in comparison to smaller species.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Relying as they do on strength rather than speed, bears have relatively short limbs with thick bones to support their bulk.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The shoulder blades and the pelvis are correspondingly massive.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The limbs are much straighter than those of the big cats as there is no need for them to flex in the same way due to the differences in their gait.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The strong forelimbs are used to catch prey, excavate dens, dig out burrowing animals, turn over rocks and logs to locate prey, and club large creatures.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Unlike most other land carnivorans, bears are plantigrade.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] They distribute their weight toward the hind feet, which makes them look lumbering when they walk.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] They are capable of bursts of speed but soon tire, and as a result mostly rely on ambush rather than the chase.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears can stand on their hind feet and sit up straight with remarkable balance.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Their front paws are flexible enough to grasp fruit and leaves.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears' non-retractable claws are used for digging, climbing, tearing, and catching prey.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The claws on the front feet are larger than those on the back and may be a hindrance when climbing trees; black bears are the most arboreal of the bears, and have the shortest claws.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Pandas are unique in having a bony extension on the wrist of the front feet which acts as a thumb, and is used for gripping bamboo shoots as the animals feed.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Most mammals have agouti hair, with each individual hair shaft having bands of color corresponding to two different types of melanin pigment.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears however have a single type of melanin and the hairs have a single color throughout their length, apart from the tip which is sometimes a different shade.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The coat consists of long guard hairs, which form a protective shaggy covering, and short dense hairs which form an insulating layer trapping air close to the skin.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The shaggy coat helps maintain body heat during winter hibernation and is shed in the spring leaving a shorter summer coat.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Polar bears have hollow, translucent guard hairs which gain heat from the sun and conduct it to the dark-colored skin below.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] They have a thick layer of blubber for extra insulation, and the soles of their feet are furry, except for the pads.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] While bears tend to be uniform in color, some species may have markings on the chest or face and the giant panda has a bold black-and-white pelage.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears have small rounded ears so as to minimize heat loss, but neither their hearing nor sight are particularly acute.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Unlike many other carnivorans they have color vision, perhaps to help them distinguish ripe nuts and fruits.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] They are unique among carnivorans in not having touch-sensitive whiskers on the muzzle; however, they have an excellent sense of smell, better than that of the dog, or possibly any other mammal.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] They use smell for signalling to each other (either to warn off rivals or detect mates) and for finding food.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Smell is the principal sense used by bears to locate most of their food, and they have excellent memories which helps them to relocate places where they have found food before.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The skulls of bears are massive, providing anchorage for the powerful masseter and temporal jaw muscles.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The canine teeth are large but mostly used for display, and the molar teeth flat and crushing.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Unlike most other members of the Carnivora, bears have relatively undeveloped carnassial teeth, and their teeth are adapted for a diet that includes a significant amount of vegetable matter.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Considerable variation occurs in dental formula even within a given species.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] This may indicate bears are still in the process of evolving from a mainly meat-eating diet to a predominantly herbivorous one.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Polar bears appear to have secondarily re-evolved carnassial-like cheek teeth, as their diets have switched back towards carnivory.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Sloth bears lack lower central incisors and use their protrusible lips for sucking up the termites on which they feed.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The structure of the larynx of bears appears to be the most basal of the caniforms.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] They possess air pouches connected to the pharynx which may amplify their vocalizations.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears have a fairly simple digestive system typical for carnivorans, with a single stomach, short undifferentiated intestines and no cecum.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Even the herbivorous giant panda still has the digestive system of a carnivore, as well as carnivore-specific genes.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Its ability to digest cellulose is ascribed to the microbes in its gut.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears must spend much of their time feeding in order to gain enough nutrition from foliage.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The panda, in particular, spends 12–15 hours a day feeding.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Extant bears are found in sixty countries primarily in the Northern Hemisphere and are concentrated in Asia, North America, and Europe.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] An exception is the spectacled bear; native to South America, it inhabits the Andean region.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The sun bear's range extends below the equator in Southeast Asia.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The Atlas bear, a subspecies of the brown bear was distributed in North Africa from Morocco to Libya, but it became extinct around the 1870s.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The most widespread species is the brown bear, which occurs from Western Europe eastwards through Asia to the western areas of North America (where the local subspecies is the grizzly bear).
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The American black bear is restricted to North America, and the polar bear is restricted to the Arctic Ocean.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] All the remaining species of bear are Asian.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] They occur in a range of habitats which include tropical lowland rainforest, both coniferous and broadleaf forests, prairies, steppes, montane grassland, alpine scree slopes, Arctic tundra and in the case of the polar bear, ice floes.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears may dig their dens in hillsides or use caves, hollow logs and dense vegetation for shelter.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Brown and American black bears are generally diurnal, meaning that they are active for the most part during the day, though they may forage substantially by night.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Other species may be nocturnal, active at night, though female sloth bears with cubs may feed more at daytime to avoid competition from conspecifics and nocturnal predators.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears are overwhelmingly solitary and are considered to be the most asocial of all the Carnivora.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The only times bears are encountered in groups are mothers with young or occasional seasonal bounties of rich food (such as salmon runs).
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Fights between males can occur and older individuals may have extensive scarring, which suggests that maintaining dominance can be intense.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] With their acute sense of smell, bears can locate carcasses from several kilometres away.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] They use olfaction to locate other foods, encounter mates, avoid rivals and recognize their cubs.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Most bears are opportunistic omnivores and consume more plant than animal matter, and appear to have evolved from an ancestor which was a low-protein macronutrient omnivore.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] They eat anything from leaves, roots, and berries to insects, carrion, fresh meat, and fish, and have digestive systems and teeth adapted to such a diet.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] At the extremes are the almost entirely herbivorous giant panda and the mostly carnivorous polar bear.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] However, all bears feed on any food source that becomes seasonally available.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] For example, Asiatic black bears in Taiwan consume large numbers of acorns when these are most common, and switch to ungulates at other times of the year.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] When foraging for plants, bears choose to eat them at the stage when they are at their most nutritious and digestible, typically avoiding older grasses, sedges and leaves.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Hence, in more northern temperate areas, browsing and grazing is more common early in spring and later becomes more restricted.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Knowing when plants are ripe for eating is a learned behavior.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Berries may be foraged in bushes or at the tops of trees, and bears try to maximize the number of berries consumed versus foliage.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] In autumn, some bear species forage large amounts of naturally fermented fruits, which affects their behavior.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Smaller bears climb trees to obtain mast (edible reproductive parts, such as acorns).
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Such masts can be very important to the diets of these species, and mast failures may result in long-range movements by bears looking for alternative food sources.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Brown bears, with their powerful digging abilities, commonly eat roots.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The panda's diet is over 99% bamboo, of 30 different species.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Its strong jaws are adapted for crushing the tough stems of these plants, though they prefer to eat the more nutritious leaves.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bromeliads can make up to 50% of the diet of the spectacled bear, which also has strong jaws to bite them open.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The sloth bear is not as specialized as polar bears and the panda, has lost several front teeth usually seen in bears, and developed a long, suctioning tongue to feed on the ants, termites, and other burrowing insects.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] At certain times of the year, these insects can make up 90% of their diets.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Some individuals become addicted to sweets in garbage inside towns where tourism-related waste is generated throughout the year.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Some species may raid the nests of wasps and bees for the honey and immature insects, in spite of stinging from the adults.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Sun bears use their long tongues to lick up both insects and honey.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Fish are an important source of food for some species, and brown bears in particular gather in large numbers at salmon runs.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Typically, a bear plunges into the water and seizes a fish with its jaws or front paws.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The preferred parts to eat are the brain and eggs.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Small burrowing mammals like rodents may be dug out and eaten.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The brown/grizzly bear and both species of black bears sometimes take large ungulates, such as deer and bovids, mostly the young and weak.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] These animals may be taken by a short rush and ambush, though hiding young may be sniffed out and pounced on.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The polar bear mainly preys on seals, stalking them from the ice or breaking into their dens.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] They primarily eat the highly digestible blubber.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Large mammalian prey is typically killed with raw strength, including bites and paw swipes, and bears do not display the specialized killing methods of felids and canids.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Predatory behavior in bears is typically taught to the young by the mother.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears are prolific scavengers and kleptoparasites, stealing food caches from rodents, and carcasses from other predators.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] For hibernating species, weight gain is important as it provides nourishment during winter dormancy.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] A brown bear can eat 41 kg (90 lb) of food and gain 2–3 kg (4.4–6.6 lb) of fat a day prior to entering its den.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears produce a number of vocal and non-vocal sounds.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Tongue-clicking, grunting or chuffing may be made in cordial situations, such as between mothers and cubs or courting couples, while moaning, huffing, snorting or blowing air is made when an individual is stressed.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Barking is produced during times of alarm, excitement or to give away the animal's position.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Warning sounds include jaw-clicking and lip-popping, while teeth-chatters, bellows, growls, roars and pulsing sounds are made in aggressive encounters.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Cubs may squeal, bawl, bleat or scream when in distress and make motor-like humming when comfortable or nursing.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears sometimes communicate with visual displays such as standing upright, which exaggerates the individual's size.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The chest markings of some species may add to this intimidating display.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Staring is an aggressive act and the facial markings of spectacled bears and giant pandas may help draw attention to the eyes during agonistic encounters.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Individuals may approach each other by stiff-legged walking with the head lowered.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Dominance between bears is asserted by making a frontal orientation, showing the canine teeth, muzzle twisting and neck stretching.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] A subordinate may respond with a lateral orientation, by turning away and dropping the head and by sitting or lying down.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears also communicate with their scent by urinating on or rubbing against trees and other objects.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] This is usually accompanied by clawing and biting the object.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bark may be spread around to draw attention to the marking post.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Pandas establish territories by marking objects with urine and a waxy substance from their anal glands.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Polar bears leave behind their scent in their tracks which allow individuals to keep track of one another in the vast Arctic wilderness.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The mating system of bears has variously been described as a form of polygyny, promiscuity and serial monogamy.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] During the breeding season, males take notice of females in their vicinity and females become more tolerant of males.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] A male bear may visit a female continuously over a period of several days or weeks, depending on the species, to test her reproductive state.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] During this time period, males try to prevent rivals from interacting with their mate.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Courtship may be brief, although in some Asian species, courting pairs may engage in wrestling, hugging, mock fighting and vocalizing.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Ovulation is induced by mating, which can last up to 30 minutes depending on the species.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Gestation typically lasts six to nine months, including delayed implantation, and litter size numbers up to four cubs.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Giant pandas may give birth to twins but they can only suckle one young and the other is left to die.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] In northern living species, birth takes place during winter dormancy.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Cubs are born blind and helpless with at most a thin layer of hair, relying on their mother for warmth.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The milk of the female bear is rich in fat and antibodies and cubs may suckle for up to a year after they are born.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] By two to three months, cubs can follow their mother outside the den.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] They usually follow her on foot, but sloth bear cubs may ride on their mother's back.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Male bears play no role in raising young.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Infanticide, where an adult male kills the cubs of another, has been recorded in polar bears, brown bears and American black bears but not in other species.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Males kill young to bring the female into estrus.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Cubs may flee and the mother defends them even at the cost of her life.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] In some species, offspring may become independent around the next spring, though some may stay until the female successfully mates again.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears reach sexual maturity shortly after they disperse; at around three to six years depending on the species.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Male Alaskan brown bears and polar bears may continue to grow until they are 11 years old.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The brown bear can live an average of 25 years.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears of northern regions, including the American black bear and the much larger grizzly bear, hibernate in the winter.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] During hibernation, the bear's metabolism slows down, its body temperature decreases by 4–7 °C (7.2–12.6 °F), and its heart rate slows from a normal value of 55 to as low as 9 beats per minute.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] In order for their heart rate to slow down to this level during hibernation, a protein found in striated muscle, like the heart, called myosin must enter a super-relaxed state.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] In the super-relaxed state, the consumption of ATP is kept very low, allowing the bear to make it through the winter without losing all of its energy due to the basic functions such as pumping blood through the body.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears normally do not wake during their hibernation, and can go the entire period without eating, drinking, urinating, or defecating.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] A fecal plug is formed in the colon, and is expelled when the bear wakes in the spring.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] If they have stored enough body fat, their muscles remain in good condition, and their protein maintenance requirements are met from recycling waste urea.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Female bears give birth during the hibernation period, and are roused when doing so.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The most important are humans, and as they started cultivating crops, they increasingly came in conflict with the bears that raided them.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Since the invention of firearms, people have been able to kill bears with greater ease.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Felids like the tiger may also prey on bears, particularly cubs, which may also be threatened by canids.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears are parasitized by eighty species of parasites, including single-celled protozoans and gastro-intestinal worms, and nematodes and flukes in their heart, liver, lungs and bloodstream.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Externally, they have ticks, fleas and lice.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] A study of American black bears found seventeen species of endoparasite including the protozoan *Sarcocystis*, the parasitic worm *Diphyllobothrium mansonoides*, and the nematodes *Dirofilaria immitis*, *Capillaria aerophila*, *Physaloptera* sp., *Strongyloides* sp. and others.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Of these, *D. mansonoides* and adult *C. aerophila* were causing pathological symptoms.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] By contrast, polar bears have few parasites; many parasitic species need a secondary, usually terrestrial, host, and the polar bear's life style is such that few alternative hosts exist in their environment.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The protozoan *Toxoplasma gondii* has been found in polar bears, and the nematode *Trichinella nativa* can cause a serious infection and decline in older polar bears.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears in North America are sometimes infected by a *Morbillivirus* similar to the canine distemper virus.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] They are susceptible to infectious canine hepatitis (CAV-1), with free-living black bears dying rapidly of encephalitis and hepatitis.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] In modern times, bears have come under pressure through encroachment on their habitats and illegal trade in bear parts, including the Asian bile bear market, though hunting is now banned, largely replaced by farming.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The IUCN lists six bear species as vulnerable; even the two least concern species, the brown bear and the American black bear, are at risk of extirpation in certain areas.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] In general, these two species inhabit remote areas with little interaction with humans, and the main non-natural causes of mortality are hunting, trapping, road-kill and depredation.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Laws have been passed in many areas of the world to protect bears from habitat destruction.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Public perception of bears is often positive, as people identify with bears due to their omnivorous diets, their ability to stand on two legs, and their symbolic importance.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Support for bear protection is widespread, at least in more affluent societies.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The giant panda has become a worldwide symbol of conservation.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The Sichuan Giant Panda Sanctuaries, which are home to around 30% of the wild panda population, gained a UNESCO World Heritage Site designation in 2006.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Where bears raid crops or attack livestock, they may come into conflict with humans.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] In poorer rural regions, attitudes may be more shaped by the dangers posed by bears, and the economic costs they cause to farmers and ranchers.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Several bear species are dangerous to humans, especially in areas where they have become used to people; elsewhere, they generally avoid humans.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Injuries caused by bears are rare, but are widely reported.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears such as grizzlies may attack humans in response to being startled, in defense of young or food, or even for predatory reasons.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears in captivity have for centuries been used for entertainment.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] They have been trained to dance, and were kept for baiting in Europe from at least the 16th century.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] There were five bear-baiting gardens in Southwark, London, at that time; archaeological remains of three of these have survived.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Across Europe, nomadic Romani bear handlers called Ursari lived by busking with their bears from the 12th century.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears have been hunted for sport, food, and folk medicine.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Their meat is dark and stringy, like a tough cut of beef.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] In Cantonese cuisine, bear paws are considered a delicacy.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bear meat should be cooked thoroughly, as it can be infected with the parasite *Trichinella spiralis*.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The peoples of eastern Asia use bears' body parts and secretions (notably their gallbladders and bile) as part of traditional Chinese medicine.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] More than 12,000 bears are thought to be kept on farms in China, Vietnam, and South Korea for the production of bile.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Trade in bear products is prohibited under CITES, but bear bile has been detected in shampoos, wine and herbal medicines sold in Canada, the United States and Australia.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears have been popular subjects in art, literature, folklore and mythology.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] The image of the mother bear was prevalent throughout societies in North America and Eurasia, based on the female's devotion and protection of her cubs.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] In many Native American cultures, the bear is a symbol of rebirth because of its hibernation and re-emergence.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] A widespread belief among cultures of North America and northern Asia associated bears with shaman; this may be based on the solitary nature of both.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] Bears have thus been thought to predict the future and shaman were believed to have been capable of transforming into bears.
[src:bear-conservation/bear] There is evidence of prehistoric bear worship, though this is disputed by archaeologists.
